018/**
019 * The Quant library provides routines that operate on arrays and collections.
020 *
021 * <p>These routines are used by the Java family of output formats. This allows invariants to be
022 * output as snippets of executable (Java) code. For example, an invariant like
023 * <pre>a[] elements &ge; 1</pre>
024 * is output (in the Java, JML, and DBC formats) as something like
025 *
026 * <pre>daikon.Quant.eltsGTE(a, 1)</pre>
027 *
028 * <h3>Naming</h3>
029 *
030 * The library methods have names of the following forms, where OP indicates an operation: Equal,
031 * NotEqual, GT (greater than), GTE (greater than or equal to), LT, LTE.
032 * <ul>
033 * <li>pairwiseOP. Apply OP to corresponding elements of two arrays:
034 *     a[0] OP b[0], a[1] OP b[1], etc.
035 * <li>eltsOP. Apply OP to each element of one array, and a scalar:
036 *     a[0] OP x, a[1] OP x, etc.
037 * <li>eltwiseOP: Apply OP to adjacent elements of one array:
038 *     a[0] OP a[1], a[1] OP a[2], etc.
039 * <li>lexOP: Determine lexical ordering:
040 *     compare two arrays pairwise, stopping as soon as the result is known.
041 * <li>eltsOPindex: Apply op to array elements and their indices:
042 *     a[0] OP 0, a[1] OP 1, etc.
043 * </ul>
044 *
045 * <h3>Equality semantics</h3>
046 *
047 * <p>Whenever a method involves comparing two elements for equality, this is always "==" equality
048 * (even for Objects and Strings).
049 *
050 * <h3>No exceptions thrown</h3>
051 *
052 * <p>The library strives not to throw exceptions, even if illegal arguments are passed to the
053 * routines. This has two consequences.
054 *
055 * <p>First, each predicate (boolean method) returns false when invoked on an illegal argument such
056 * as a null collection (array or Collection).
057 *
058 * <p>Second, each accessor method returns a default "bad" value if inovked on an illegal argument.
059 * For example, the default value for the double type is Double.NaN.
060 *
061 * <p>The rationale for the decision to never throw exceptions is that we wish to be able to invoke
062 * the Quant methods at run time without distrubing execution of a program, and without forcing
063 * clients to write a try .. catch block around each invocation.
064 *
065 * <p>A downside of the decision is that if the default value is returned, it may be impossible for
066 * a client to determine whether the method really returned that value, or whether the invocation
067 * involved an illegal argument. To avoid this problem, it is generally better to use a Quant
068 * library predicate rather than returning a value and then testing it externally.
069 */
070public final class Quant {
071  private Quant() { throw new Error("do not instantiate"); }

347  /** Returns a subsequence of seq with first elements seq[start] and last element seq[end]. */
348  @Pure
349  public static boolean @PolyNull [] slice(boolean @PolyNull [] seq, int start, int end) {
350    if (seq == null) {
351      return null;
352    }
353    int sliceStart = start;
354    int sliceEnd = end;
355    if (start < 0) {
356      return new boolean[] { };
357    }
358    if (end > seq.length - 1) {
359      return new boolean[] { };
360    }
361    if (sliceStart > sliceEnd) {
362      return new boolean[] { };
363    }
364    int length = sliceEnd - sliceStart + 1;
365    return ArraysPlume.subarray(seq, sliceStart, length);
366  }

547  /**
548   * collectboolean accepts an object and a list of fields (one of which is of array type, and the
549   * rest of which are not), and produces an array in which the original object has had the given
550   * fields accessed.
551   *
552   * <p>Daikon creates invariants over "variables" such as the following.
553   *
554   * <dl>
555   * <dt>x.arr[].z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements y.z
556   *              for all y's in array x.arr.</dd>
557   * <dt>arr[].y.z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements x.y.z
558   *              for all x's in array arr.</dd>
559   * <dt>x.y.z[]</dt>   <dd>The result of collecting all elements in array x.y.z[]</dd>
560   * </dl>
561   *
562   * <p>The collectboolean() method does this collecting work.
563   *
564   * <p>Given an object (x, arr, or x, correspondingly, in the above examples) and a "field string"
565   * (arr.z, y.z, or y.z, correspondingly, in the above example), the collect method collects the
566   * elements that result from following the fields, one of which is assumed to be an array.
567   *
568   * <p>
569   * requires: fieldStr.length() &gt; 0 and object != null
570   * <p>
571   * requires: fieldStr contains only field names, no "[]" strings.
572   * <p>
573   * requires: the method only works for field sequences with exactly one field representing an
574   * array. For example, the collection a[].b[].c will fail.
575   *
576   * @return if the resulting collection is of non-primitive type, then returns an array of type
577   * Object[]. Returns null if any array or field access causes an exception.
578   */
579
580  @SideEffectFree
581  public static boolean @Nullable [] collectboolean(@Nullable Object object, @Nullable String fieldStr) {
582
583    if (object == null) {
584      return null;
585    }
586    if (fieldStr == null) {
587      return null;
588    }
589
590    // assert fieldStr != null && !"".equals(fieldStr);
591    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
592    boolean[] retval = collectboolean(object, fieldNames, 0);
593    // System.err.println("%%% fieldArray returned: " + plume.Arrays.toString(retval));
594    return retval;
595  }
596
597  /** Helper method for collectboolean(Object, String).
598   * Operates on a subset of the fields: those in fields[fieldsStartIdx..].
599   * @see collectboolean(Object, String)
600   */
601  // @PolyNull does not work for return type, because null is returned on error.
602  @SideEffectFree
603  private static boolean @Nullable [] collectboolean(@Nullable Object object,
604                                                   String[] fields, int fieldsStartIdx) {
605
606    if (object == null) {
607      return null;
608    }
609    assert (fields != null);
610    assert (fieldsStartIdx >= 0 && fieldsStartIdx < fields.length);
611
612    Object fieldObj;
613    try {
614      Field field = (object instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
615        ? ((Class<?>)object).getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx])
616        : object.getClass().getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx]);
617      field.setAccessible(true);
618      // Class cls = field.getType();
619      fieldObj = field.get(object);
620      // System.out.println("***fieldObj="+fieldObj);
621
622    } catch (Exception e) {
623      return null;
624
625    }
626
627    if (fieldObj == null) {
628      return null;
629    }
630
631    // base case: just accessed the last field
632    if (fields.length - 1 == fieldsStartIdx) {
633
634      if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
635        // last field is an array
636        return (boolean[])fieldObj;
637      } else {
638        // This hack should be removed in favor of, at "oneEltArray = ..."
639        // below, calling a version of collectboolean_field that throws an
640        // error.  Then, this case becomes a run-time error.  -MDE
641
642        // Just one element; return a one-element array.
643        // assert cls.equals(Boolean.TYPE);
644        return new boolean[] { ((Boolean)fieldObj).booleanValue() };
645      }
646    } else {
647      // recursive case: more fields to access after this one
648
649      if (daikon.ProglangType.list_implementors.contains(fieldObj.getClass().getName())) {
650
651        java.util.AbstractCollection<?> collection = (java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)fieldObj;
652        boolean[] intermediate = new boolean[collection.size()];
653        int index = 0;
654        for (Iterator<?> i = collection.iterator() ; i.hasNext() ; ) {
655          Object obj = i.next();
656          boolean[] oneEltArray = collectboolean(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
657          if (oneEltArray == null) {
658            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
659          }
660          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
661          intermediate[index++] = oneEltArray[0];
662        }
663        return intermediate;
664      } else if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
665
666        // collect elements across array
667        boolean[] intermediate = new boolean[Array.getLength(fieldObj)];
668        for (int i = 0 ; i < intermediate.length ; i++) {
669          Object obj = Array.get(fieldObj, i);
670          boolean[] oneEltArray = collectboolean(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
671          if (oneEltArray == null) {
672            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
673          }
674          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
675          intermediate[i] = oneEltArray[0];
676        }
677        return intermediate;
678      } else {
679
680        return collectboolean(fieldObj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
681      }
682    }
683  }
684
685  /**
686   * Returns the results of dereferencing the fields for 'object'. For example, the call
687   *
688   * <pre>collectboolean_field(x, "f.g.h")</pre>
689   *
690   * has the same value as
691   *
692   * <pre>x.f.g.h</pre>.
693   * Returns a default value if any field access causes an exception.
694   */
695  @SideEffectFree
696  public static boolean collectboolean_field(Object object, String fieldStr) {
697
698    if (object == null) {
699      return false; // return default value
700    }
701    if (fieldStr == null) {
702      return false; // return default value
703    }
704
705    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
706
707    // Holds the intermediate (and final) result
708    Object fieldObj = object;
709
710    for (int i = 0 ; i < fieldNames.length ; i++) {
711
712      String fieldName = fieldNames[i];
713
714      try {
715        Field field =
716          (fieldObj instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
717          ? ((Class<?>)fieldObj).getDeclaredField(fieldName)
718          : fieldObj.getClass().getDeclaredField(fieldName);
719        field.setAccessible(true);
720        fieldObj = field.get(fieldObj);
721
722        if (fieldObj == null) {
723          return false; // return default value
724        }
725
726      } catch (Exception e) {
727        return false; // return default value
728
729      }
730
731    }
732
733    return ((Boolean)fieldObj).booleanValue();
734  }

740  /**
741   * Returns the ith element of the array or collection argument. If the argument is null or not an
742   * array or collection, returns a default value (Byte.MAX_VALUE).
743   */
744
745  @Pure
746  public static byte getElement_byte(Object o, long i) {
747    if (o == null) {
748      return Byte.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
749    }
750    java.lang.Class<?> c = o.getClass();
751    if (c.isArray()) {
752      return java.lang.reflect.Array.getByte(o, (int)i);
753    } else if (o instanceof java.util.AbstractCollection<?>) {
754      return java.lang.reflect.Array.getByte(((java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)o).toArray(), (int)i);
755    } else {
756      return Byte.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
757    }
758  }
759
760  @Pure
761  public static byte getElement_byte(byte[] arr, long i) {
762    if (arr == null) {
763      return Byte.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
764    }
765    return arr[(int)i];
766  }

810  /** True iff both sequences have the same length, and all seq2[i] divide seq1[i].
811   *
812   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
813   *
814   * <pre>
815   * /\ seq1.length == seq2.length
816   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq2.length-1 } : seq2[i] divides seq1[i]
817   * </pre>
818   *
819   */
820  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
821  @Pure
822  public static boolean pairwiseDivides(byte[] seq1, byte[] seq2) {
823    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
824      return false;
825    }
826    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
827    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
828      if (ne(seq1[i] % seq2[i], 0)) {
829        return false;
830      }
831    }
832    return true;
833  }

891  /**
892   * Returns the array { seq1[0], ..., seq1[seq1.length-1], seq2[0], ... , seq2[seq2.length-1] } .
893   *
894   * <p>If either array is null, returns null. If either array is empty, returns only those
895   * elements in the other array. If both arrays are empty, returns a new empty array.
896   */
897  @SideEffectFree
898  public static byte @PolyNull [] concat(byte @PolyNull [] seq1, byte @PolyNull [] seq2) {
899    if (seq1 == null) {
900      return null;
901    }
902    if (seq2 == null) {
903      return null;
904    }
905    return ArraysPlume.concat(seq1, seq2);
906  }
907
908  @SideEffectFree
909  public static int @PolyNull [] concat(byte @PolyNull [] seq1, int @PolyNull [] seq2) {
910    if (seq1 == null) {
911      return null;
912    }
913    if (seq2 == null) {
914      return null;
915    }
916    // Cannot just use ArraysPlume.concat because the two arrays
917    // have different types.  This essentially inlines that method.
918    int newLength = seq1.length + seq2.length;
919    int[] retval = new int[newLength];
920
921    for (int j = 0 ; j < seq1.length ; j++) {
922      retval[j] = seq1[j];
923    }
924    System.arraycopy(seq2, 0, retval, seq1.length, seq2.length);
925
926    return retval;
927  }

956  /**
957   * Returns an array that is equivalent to the set intersection of seq1 and seq2. This method
958   * gives no assurances about the order or repetition of elements: elements may be repeated, and
959   * their order may be different from the order of elements in seq1 and seq2.
960   */
961  @Pure
962  public static byte @PolyNull [] intersection(byte @PolyNull [] seq1, byte @PolyNull [] seq2) {
963    if (seq1 == null) {
964      return null;
965    }
966    if (seq2 == null) {
967      return null;
968    }
969    byte[] intermediate = new byte[Math.min(seq1.length, seq2.length)];
970    int length = 0;
971    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
972      if (memberOf(seq1[i], seq2) ) {
973        intermediate[length++] = seq1[i];
974      }
975    }
976    return ArraysPlume.subarray(intermediate, 0, length);
977  }

1213  /** Returns a subsequence of seq with first elements seq[start] and last element seq[end]. */
1214  @Pure
1215  public static byte @PolyNull [] slice(byte @PolyNull [] seq, int start, int end) {
1216    if (seq == null) {
1217      return null;
1218    }
1219    int sliceStart = start;
1220    int sliceEnd = end;
1221    if (start < 0) {
1222      return new byte[] { };
1223    }
1224    if (end > seq.length - 1) {
1225      return new byte[] { };
1226    }
1227    if (sliceStart > sliceEnd) {
1228      return new byte[] { };
1229    }
1230    int length = sliceEnd - sliceStart + 1;
1231    return ArraysPlume.subarray(seq, sliceStart, length);
1232  }

1457  /** True iff seq1 and seq2 have the same length, and every seq1[i] == seq2[i].
1458   *
1459   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
1460   *
1461   * /\ seq1.length == se2.length
1462   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq1.length-1 } : seq1[i] == seq2[i]
1463   *
1464   */
1465
1466  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
1467  @Pure
1468  public static boolean pairwiseEqual(byte @Nullable [] seq1, byte @Nullable [] seq2) {
1469    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
1470      return false;
1471    }
1472    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
1473    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
1474      if (ne(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
1475        return false;
1476      }
1477    }
1478    return true;
1479  }

1736  /** Returns true iff seq1 is lexically &lt;  seq2. */
1737  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
1738  @Pure
1739  public static boolean lexLT(byte @Nullable [] seq1, byte @Nullable [] seq2) {
1740    if (seq1 == null) {
1741      return false;
1742    }
1743    if (seq2 == null) {
1744      return false;
1745    }
1746    int minlength = (seq1.length < seq2.length) ? seq1.length : seq2.length;
1747    for (int i = 0 ; i < minlength ; i++) {
1748      if (gt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
1749        return false;
1750      } else if (lt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
1751        return true;
1752      }
1753    }
1754    if (seq1.length >= seq2.length) {
1755      return false;
1756    }
1757    return true;
1758  }

1929   *

1932  @Pure
1933  public static boolean eltwiseEqual(byte @Nullable [] seq) {
1934  if (seq == null) {
1935    return false;

1939        if (ne(seq[i], seq[i + 1])) {
1940          return false;
1941        }
1942      }
1943    }
1944    return true;
1945  }

2023  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression="#1")

2027    return false;
2028  }
2029    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq.length ; i++) {
2030      if (i < seq.length - 1) {
2031        if (lte(seq[i], seq[i + 1])) {
2032          return false;
2033        }
2034      }
2035    }
2036    return true;

2188  /// Deferencing (accessing) fields
2189
2190  /**
2191   * collectbyte accepts an object and a list of fields (one of which is of array type, and the
2192   * rest of which are not), and produces an array in which the original object has had the given
2193   * fields accessed.
2194   *
2195   * <p>Daikon creates invariants over "variables" such as the following.
2196   *
2197   * <dl>
2198   * <dt>x.arr[].z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements y.z
2199   *              for all y's in array x.arr.</dd>
2200   * <dt>arr[].y.z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements x.y.z
2201   *              for all x's in array arr.</dd>
2202   * <dt>x.y.z[]</dt>   <dd>The result of collecting all elements in array x.y.z[]</dd>
2203   * </dl>
2204   *
2205   * <p>The collectbyte() method does this collecting work.
2206   *
2207   * <p>Given an object (x, arr, or x, correspondingly, in the above examples) and a "field string"
2208   * (arr.z, y.z, or y.z, correspondingly, in the above example), the collect method collects the
2209   * elements that result from following the fields, one of which is assumed to be an array.
2210   *
2211   * <p>
2212   * requires: fieldStr.length() &gt; 0 and object != null
2213   * <p>
2214   * requires: fieldStr contains only field names, no "[]" strings.
2215   * <p>
2216   * requires: the method only works for field sequences with exactly one field representing an
2217   * array. For example, the collection a[].b[].c will fail.
2218   *
2219   * @return if the resulting collection is of non-primitive type, then returns an array of type
2220   * Object[]. Returns null if any array or field access causes an exception.
2221   */
2222
2223  @SideEffectFree
2224  public static byte @Nullable [] collectbyte(@Nullable Object object, @Nullable String fieldStr) {
2225
2226    if (object == null) {
2227      return null;
2228    }
2229    if (fieldStr == null) {
2230      return null;
2231    }
2232
2233    // assert fieldStr != null && !"".equals(fieldStr);
2234    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
2235    byte[] retval = collectbyte(object, fieldNames, 0);
2236    // System.err.println("%%% fieldArray returned: " + plume.Arrays.toString(retval));
2237    return retval;
2238  }
2239
2240  /** Helper method for collectbyte(Object, String).
2241   * Operates on a subset of the fields: those in fields[fieldsStartIdx..].
2242   * @see collectbyte(Object, String)
2243   */
2244  // @PolyNull does not work for return type, because null is returned on error.
2245  @SideEffectFree
2246  private static byte @Nullable [] collectbyte(@Nullable Object object,
2247                                                   String[] fields, int fieldsStartIdx) {
2248
2249    if (object == null) {
2250      return null;
2251    }
2252    assert (fields != null);
2253    assert (fieldsStartIdx >= 0 && fieldsStartIdx < fields.length);
2254
2255    Object fieldObj;
2256    try {
2257      Field field = (object instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
2258        ? ((Class<?>)object).getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx])
2259        : object.getClass().getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx]);
2260      field.setAccessible(true);
2261      // Class cls = field.getType();
2262      fieldObj = field.get(object);
2263      // System.out.println("***fieldObj="+fieldObj);
2264
2265    } catch (Exception e) {
2266      return null;
2267
2268    }
2269
2270    if (fieldObj == null) {
2271      return null;
2272    }
2273
2274    // base case: just accessed the last field
2275    if (fields.length - 1 == fieldsStartIdx) {
2276
2277      if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
2278        // last field is an array
2279        return (byte[])fieldObj;
2280      } else {
2281        // This hack should be removed in favor of, at "oneEltArray = ..."
2282        // below, calling a version of collectbyte_field that throws an
2283        // error.  Then, this case becomes a run-time error.  -MDE
2284
2285        // Just one element; return a one-element array.
2286        // assert cls.equals(Byte.TYPE);
2287        return new byte[] { ((Byte)fieldObj).byteValue() };
2288      }
2289    } else {
2290      // recursive case: more fields to access after this one
2291
2292      if (daikon.ProglangType.list_implementors.contains(fieldObj.getClass().getName())) {
2293
2294        java.util.AbstractCollection<?> collection = (java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)fieldObj;
2295        byte[] intermediate = new byte[collection.size()];
2296        int index = 0;
2297        for (Iterator<?> i = collection.iterator() ; i.hasNext() ; ) {
2298          Object obj = i.next();
2299          byte[] oneEltArray = collectbyte(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
2300          if (oneEltArray == null) {
2301            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
2302          }
2303          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
2304          intermediate[index++] = oneEltArray[0];
2305        }
2306        return intermediate;
2307      } else if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
2308
2309        // collect elements across array
2310        byte[] intermediate = new byte[Array.getLength(fieldObj)];
2311        for (int i = 0 ; i < intermediate.length ; i++) {
2312          Object obj = Array.get(fieldObj, i);
2313          byte[] oneEltArray = collectbyte(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
2314          if (oneEltArray == null) {
2315            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
2316          }
2317          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
2318          intermediate[i] = oneEltArray[0];
2319        }
2320        return intermediate;
2321      } else {
2322
2323        return collectbyte(fieldObj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
2324      }
2325    }
2326  }
2327
2328  /**
2329   * Returns the results of dereferencing the fields for 'object'. For example, the call
2330   *
2331   * <pre>collectbyte_field(x, "f.g.h")</pre>
2332   *
2333   * has the same value as
2334   *
2335   * <pre>x.f.g.h</pre>.
2336   * Returns a default value if any field access causes an exception.
2337   */
2338  @SideEffectFree
2339  public static byte collectbyte_field(Object object, String fieldStr) {
2340
2341    if (object == null) {
2342      return Byte.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
2343    }
2344    if (fieldStr == null) {
2345      return Byte.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
2346    }
2347
2348    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
2349
2350    // Holds the intermediate (and final) result
2351    Object fieldObj = object;
2352
2353    for (int i = 0 ; i < fieldNames.length ; i++) {
2354
2355      String fieldName = fieldNames[i];
2356
2357      try {
2358        Field field =
2359          (fieldObj instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
2360          ? ((Class<?>)fieldObj).getDeclaredField(fieldName)
2361          : fieldObj.getClass().getDeclaredField(fieldName);
2362        field.setAccessible(true);
2363        fieldObj = field.get(fieldObj);
2364
2365        if (fieldObj == null) {
2366          return Byte.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
2367        }
2368
2369      } catch (Exception e) {
2370        return Byte.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
2371
2372      }
2373
2374    }
2375
2376    return ((Byte)fieldObj).byteValue();
2377  }

2383  /**
2384   * Returns the ith element of the array or collection argument. If the argument is null or not an
2385   * array or collection, returns a default value (Character.MAX_VALUE).
2386   */
2387
2388  @Pure
2389  public static char getElement_char(Object o, long i) {
2390    if (o == null) {
2391      return Character.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
2392    }
2393    java.lang.Class<?> c = o.getClass();
2394    if (c.isArray()) {
2395      return java.lang.reflect.Array.getChar(o, (int)i);
2396    } else if (o instanceof java.util.AbstractCollection<?>) {
2397      return java.lang.reflect.Array.getChar(((java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)o).toArray(), (int)i);
2398    } else {
2399      return Character.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
2400    }
2401  }

2408    return arr[(int)i];
2409  }

2464   * order may be different from the order of elements in seq1 and seq2.

2477  /**
2478   * Returns an array that is equivalent to the set intersection of seq1 and seq2. This method
2479   * gives no assurances about the order or repetition of elements: elements may be repeated, and
2480   * their order may be different from the order of elements in seq1 and seq2.
2481   */
2482  @Pure
2483  public static char @PolyNull [] intersection(char @PolyNull [] seq1, char @PolyNull [] seq2) {
2484    if (seq1 == null) {
2485      return null;
2486    }
2487    if (seq2 == null) {
2488      return null;
2489    }
2490    char[] intermediate = new char[Math.min(seq1.length, seq2.length)];
2491    int length = 0;
2492    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
2493      if (memberOf(seq1[i], seq2) ) {
2494        intermediate[length++] = seq1[i];
2495      }
2496    }
2497    return ArraysPlume.subarray(intermediate, 0, length);
2498  }

2500  /**

2503   * order may be different from the order of elements in seq1 and seq2.
2504   */
2505  @Pure
2506  public static char @PolyNull [] setDiff(char @PolyNull [] seq1, char @PolyNull [] seq2) {
2507    if (seq1 == null) {
2508      return null;
2509    }
2510    if (seq2 == null) {
2511      return null;
2512    }
2513    char[] intermediate = new char[seq1.length];
2514    int length = 0;
2515    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
2516      if (!memberOf(seq1[i], seq2)) {
2517        intermediate[length++] = seq1[i];
2518      }
2519    }
2520    return ArraysPlume.subarray(intermediate, 0, length);

2523  /** Returns true iff seq1 and seq2 are equal when considered as sets. */
2524  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
2525  @Pure
2526  public static boolean setEqual(char @Nullable [] seq1, char @Nullable [] seq2) {
2527    if (seq1 == null) {
2528      return false;
2529    }
2530    if (seq2 == null) {
2531      return false;
2532    }
2533    for (int i = 0; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
2534      if (!memberOf(seq1[i], seq2) ) {
2535        return false;
2536      }
2537    }
2538    for (int i = 0; i < seq2.length ; i++) {
2539      if (!memberOf(seq2[i], seq1) ) {
2540        return false;
2541      }
2542    }
2543    return true;
2544  }

2546  /** True iff seq1 is the reverse of seq2.
2547   *
2548   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
2549   *
2550   * <pre>
2551   * /\ seq1.length == seq2.length
2552   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq1.length-1 } : seq1[i] == seq2[seq2.length-1-i]
2553   * </pre>
2554   *
2555   */
2556  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
2557  @Pure
2558  public static boolean isReverse(char[] seq1, char[] seq2) {
2559    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
2560      return false;
2561    }
2562    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
2563    int length = seq1.length;
2564    for (int i = 0 ; i < length ; i++) {
2565      if (ne(seq1[i], seq2[length - i - 1])) {
2566        return false;
2567      }
2568    }
2569    return true;
2570  }

2600 /** Returns true iff elt is in array arr. */
2601  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression="#2")
2602  @Pure
2603  public static boolean memberOf(char elt, char @Nullable [] arr) {
2604    if (arr == null) {
2605      return false;
2606    }
2607    for (int i = 0 ; i < arr.length ; i++) {
2608      if (eq(arr[i], elt)) {
2609        return true;
2610      }
2611    }
2612    return false;

2615  /** Returns a subsequence of seq with first elements seq[start] and last element seq[end]. */
2616  @Pure
2617  public static char @PolyNull [] slice(char @PolyNull [] seq, int start, int end) {
2618    if (seq == null) {
2619      return null;
2620    }
2621    int sliceStart = start;
2622    int sliceEnd = end;
2623    if (start < 0) {
2624      return new char[] { };
2625    }
2626    if (end > seq.length - 1) {
2627      return new char[] { };
2628    }
2629    if (sliceStart > sliceEnd) {
2630      return new char[] { };
2631    }
2632    int length = sliceEnd - sliceStart + 1;
2633    return ArraysPlume.subarray(seq, sliceStart, length);
2634  }

2775  /** True iff seq1 and seq2 have the same length, and every seq1[i] == seq2[i].
2776   *
2777   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
2778   *
2779   * /\ seq1.length == se2.length
2780   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq1.length-1 } : seq1[i] == seq2[i]
2781   *
2782   */
2783
2784  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
2785  @Pure
2786  public static boolean pairwiseEqual(char @Nullable [] seq1, char @Nullable [] seq2) {
2787    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
2788      return false;
2789    }
2790    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
2791    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
2792      if (ne(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
2793        return false;
2794      }
2795    }
2796    return true;
2797  }

2919      return false;
2920    }
2921    if (seq2 == null) {
2922      return false;
2923    }
2924    return pairwiseEqual(seq1, seq2);
2925  }

2939
2940  /** Returns true iff seq1 is lexically &lt;  seq2. */
2941  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
2942  @Pure
2943  public static boolean lexLT(char @Nullable [] seq1, char @Nullable [] seq2) {
2944    if (seq1 == null) {
2945      return false;
2946    }
2947    if (seq2 == null) {
2948      return false;
2949    }
2950    int minlength = (seq1.length < seq2.length) ? seq1.length : seq2.length;
2951    for (int i = 0 ; i < minlength ; i++) {
2952      if (gt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
2953        return false;
2954      } else if (lt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
2955        return true;
2956      }
2957    }
2958    if (seq1.length >= seq2.length) {
2959      return false;
2960    }
2961    return true;
2962  }

3300  /// Deferencing (accessing) fields
3301
3302  /**
3303   * collectchar accepts an object and a list of fields (one of which is of array type, and the
3304   * rest of which are not), and produces an array in which the original object has had the given
3305   * fields accessed.
3306   *
3307   * <p>Daikon creates invariants over "variables" such as the following.
3308   *
3309   * <dl>
3310   * <dt>x.arr[].z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements y.z
3311   *              for all y's in array x.arr.</dd>
3312   * <dt>arr[].y.z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements x.y.z
3313   *              for all x's in array arr.</dd>
3314   * <dt>x.y.z[]</dt>   <dd>The result of collecting all elements in array x.y.z[]</dd>
3315   * </dl>
3316   *
3317   * <p>The collectchar() method does this collecting work.
3318   *
3319   * <p>Given an object (x, arr, or x, correspondingly, in the above examples) and a "field string"
3320   * (arr.z, y.z, or y.z, correspondingly, in the above example), the collect method collects the
3321   * elements that result from following the fields, one of which is assumed to be an array.
3322   *
3323   * <p>
3324   * requires: fieldStr.length() &gt; 0 and object != null
3325   * <p>
3326   * requires: fieldStr contains only field names, no "[]" strings.
3327   * <p>
3328   * requires: the method only works for field sequences with exactly one field representing an
3329   * array. For example, the collection a[].b[].c will fail.
3330   *
3331   * @return if the resulting collection is of non-primitive type, then returns an array of type
3332   * Object[]. Returns null if any array or field access causes an exception.
3333   */
3334
3335  @SideEffectFree
3336  public static char @Nullable [] collectchar(@Nullable Object object, @Nullable String fieldStr) {
3337
3338    if (object == null) {
3339      return null;
3340    }
3341    if (fieldStr == null) {
3342      return null;
3343    }
3344
3345    // assert fieldStr != null && !"".equals(fieldStr);
3346    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
3347    char[] retval = collectchar(object, fieldNames, 0);
3348    // System.err.println("%%% fieldArray returned: " + plume.Arrays.toString(retval));
3349    return retval;
3350  }
3351
3352  /** Helper method for collectchar(Object, String).
3353   * Operates on a subset of the fields: those in fields[fieldsStartIdx..].
3354   * @see collectchar(Object, String)
3355   */
3356  // @PolyNull does not work for return type, because null is returned on error.
3357  @SideEffectFree
3358  private static char @Nullable [] collectchar(@Nullable Object object,
3359                                                   String[] fields, int fieldsStartIdx) {
3360
3361    if (object == null) {
3362      return null;
3363    }
3364    assert (fields != null);
3365    assert (fieldsStartIdx >= 0 && fieldsStartIdx < fields.length);
3366
3367    Object fieldObj;
3368    try {
3369      Field field = (object instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
3370        ? ((Class<?>)object).getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx])
3371        : object.getClass().getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx]);
3372      field.setAccessible(true);
3373      // Class cls = field.getType();
3374      fieldObj = field.get(object);
3375      // System.out.println("***fieldObj="+fieldObj);
3376
3377    } catch (Exception e) {
3378      return null;
3379
3380    }
3381
3382    if (fieldObj == null) {
3383      return null;
3384    }
3385
3386    // base case: just accessed the last field
3387    if (fields.length - 1 == fieldsStartIdx) {
3388
3389      if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
3390        // last field is an array
3391        return (char[])fieldObj;
3392      } else {
3393        // This hack should be removed in favor of, at "oneEltArray = ..."
3394        // below, calling a version of collectchar_field that throws an
3395        // error.  Then, this case becomes a run-time error.  -MDE
3396
3397        // Just one element; return a one-element array.
3398        // assert cls.equals(Character.TYPE);
3399        return new char[] { ((Character)fieldObj).charValue() };
3400      }
3401    } else {
3402      // recursive case: more fields to access after this one
3403
3404      if (daikon.ProglangType.list_implementors.contains(fieldObj.getClass().getName())) {
3405
3406        java.util.AbstractCollection<?> collection = (java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)fieldObj;
3407        char[] intermediate = new char[collection.size()];
3408        int index = 0;
3409        for (Iterator<?> i = collection.iterator() ; i.hasNext() ; ) {
3410          Object obj = i.next();
3411          char[] oneEltArray = collectchar(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
3412          if (oneEltArray == null) {
3413            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
3414          }
3415          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
3416          intermediate[index++] = oneEltArray[0];
3417        }
3418        return intermediate;
3419      } else if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
3420
3421        // collect elements across array
3422        char[] intermediate = new char[Array.getLength(fieldObj)];
3423        for (int i = 0 ; i < intermediate.length ; i++) {
3424          Object obj = Array.get(fieldObj, i);
3425          char[] oneEltArray = collectchar(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
3426          if (oneEltArray == null) {
3427            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
3428          }
3429          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
3430          intermediate[i] = oneEltArray[0];
3431        }
3432        return intermediate;
3433      } else {
3434
3435        return collectchar(fieldObj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
3436      }
3437    }
3438  }
3439
3440  /**
3441   * Returns the results of dereferencing the fields for 'object'. For example, the call
3442   *
3443   * <pre>collectchar_field(x, "f.g.h")</pre>
3444   *
3445   * has the same value as
3446   *
3447   * <pre>x.f.g.h</pre>.
3448   * Returns a default value if any field access causes an exception.
3449   */
3450  @SideEffectFree
3451  public static char collectchar_field(Object object, String fieldStr) {
3452
3453    if (object == null) {
3454      return Character.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
3455    }
3456    if (fieldStr == null) {
3457      return Character.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
3458    }
3459
3460    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
3461
3462    // Holds the intermediate (and final) result
3463    Object fieldObj = object;
3464
3465    for (int i = 0 ; i < fieldNames.length ; i++) {
3466
3467      String fieldName = fieldNames[i];
3468
3469      try {
3470        Field field =
3471          (fieldObj instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
3472          ? ((Class<?>)fieldObj).getDeclaredField(fieldName)
3473          : fieldObj.getClass().getDeclaredField(fieldName);
3474        field.setAccessible(true);
3475        fieldObj = field.get(fieldObj);
3476
3477        if (fieldObj == null) {
3478          return Character.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
3479        }
3480
3481      } catch (Exception e) {
3482        return Character.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
3483
3484      }
3485
3486    }
3487
3488    return ((Character)fieldObj).charValue();
3489  }

3495  /**
3496   * Returns the ith element of the array or collection argument. If the argument is null or not an
3497   * array or collection, returns a default value (Double.NaN).
3498   */
3499
3500  @Pure
3501  public static double getElement_double(Object o, long i) {
3502    if (o == null) {
3503      return Double.NaN; // return default value
3504    }
3505    java.lang.Class<?> c = o.getClass();
3506    if (c.isArray()) {
3507      return java.lang.reflect.Array.getDouble(o, (int)i);
3508    } else if (o instanceof java.util.AbstractCollection<?>) {
3509      return java.lang.reflect.Array.getDouble(((java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)o).toArray(), (int)i);
3510    } else {
3511      return Double.NaN; // return default value
3512    }
3513  }

3517    if (arr == null) {
3518      return Double.NaN; // return default value
3519    }
3520    return arr[(int)i];
3521  }

3566   *
3567   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
3568   *
3569   * <pre>
3570   * /\ seq1.length == seq2.length
3571   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq2.length-1 } : seq2[i] divides seq1[i]
3572   * </pre>
3573   *
3574   */
3575  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
3576  @Pure
3577  public static boolean pairwiseDivides(double[] seq1, double[] seq2) {
3578    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
3579      return false;
3580    }
3581    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
3582    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
3583      if (ne(seq1[i] % seq2[i], 0)) {
3584        return false;
3585      }
3586    }
3587    return true;
3588  }

3646  /**
3647   * Returns the array { seq1[0], ..., seq1[seq1.length-1], seq2[0], ... , seq2[seq2.length-1] } .
3648   *
3649   * <p>If either array is null, returns null. If either array is empty, returns only those
3650   * elements in the other array. If both arrays are empty, returns a new empty array.
3651   */
3652  @SideEffectFree
3653  public static double @PolyNull [] concat(double @PolyNull [] seq1, double @PolyNull [] seq2) {
3654    if (seq1 == null) {
3655      return null;
3656    }
3657    if (seq2 == null) {
3658      return null;
3659    }
3660    return ArraysPlume.concat(seq1, seq2);
3661  }
3662
3663  @SideEffectFree
3664  public static double @PolyNull [] concat(double @PolyNull [] seq1, float @PolyNull [] seq2) {
3665    if (seq1 == null) {
3666      return null;
3667    }
3668    if (seq2 == null) {
3669      return null;
3670    }
3671    // Cannot just use ArraysPlume.concat because the two arrays
3672    // have different types.  This essentially inlines that method.
3673    int newLength = seq1.length + seq2.length;
3674    double[] retval = new double[newLength];
3675
3676    System.arraycopy(seq1, 0, retval, 0, seq1.length);
3677    for (int j = 0 ; j < seq2.length ; j++) {
3678      retval[seq1.length + j] = seq2[j];
3679    }
3680
3681    return retval;
3682  }

3716  @Pure
3717  public static double @PolyNull [] intersection(double @PolyNull [] seq1, double @PolyNull [] seq2) {
3718    if (seq1 == null) {
3719      return null;
3720    }

3722      return null;
3723    }
3724    double[] intermediate = new double[Math.min(seq1.length, seq2.length)];
3725    int length = 0;

3727      if (memberOf(seq1[i], seq2) ) {
3728        intermediate[length++] = seq1[i];
3729      }
3730    }
3731    return ArraysPlume.subarray(intermediate, 0, length);
3732  }

3954  /** Returns a subsequence of seq with first elements seq[start] and last element seq[end]. */
3955  @Pure
3956  public static double @PolyNull [] slice(double @PolyNull [] seq, int start, int end) {
3957    if (seq == null) {
3958      return null;
3959    }
3960    int sliceStart = start;
3961    int sliceEnd = end;
3962    if (start < 0) {
3963      return new double[] { };
3964    }
3965    if (end > seq.length - 1) {
3966      return new double[] { };
3967    }
3968    if (sliceStart > sliceEnd) {
3969      return new double[] { };
3970    }
3971    int length = sliceEnd - sliceStart + 1;
3972    return ArraysPlume.subarray(seq, sliceStart, length);
3973  }

4198  /** True iff seq1 and seq2 have the same length, and every seq1[i] == seq2[i].
4199   *
4200   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
4201   *
4202   * /\ seq1.length == se2.length
4203   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq1.length-1 } : seq1[i] == seq2[i]
4204   *
4205   */
4206
4207  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
4208  @Pure
4209  public static boolean pairwiseEqual(double @Nullable [] seq1, double @Nullable [] seq2) {
4210    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
4211      return false;
4212    }
4213    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
4214    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
4215      if (Double.isNaN(seq1[i]) && Double.isNaN(seq2[i])) {
4216        continue;
4217      }
4218      if (ne(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
4219        return false;
4220      }
4221    }
4222    return true;
4223  }

4480  /** Returns true iff seq1 is lexically &lt;  seq2. */
4481  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
4482  @Pure
4483  public static boolean lexLT(double @Nullable [] seq1, double @Nullable [] seq2) {
4484    if (seq1 == null) {
4485      return false;
4486    }
4487    if (seq2 == null) {
4488      return false;
4489    }
4490    int minlength = (seq1.length < seq2.length) ? seq1.length : seq2.length;
4491    for (int i = 0 ; i < minlength ; i++) {
4492      if (gt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
4493        return false;
4494      } else if (lt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
4495        return true;
4496      }
4497    }
4498    if (seq1.length >= seq2.length) {
4499      return false;
4500    }
4501    return true;
4502  }

4633      if (lt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
4634        return false;
4635      } else if (gt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
4636        return true;
4637      }
4638    }
4639    if (seq1.length < seq2.length) {
4640      return false;
4641    }
4642    return true;
4643  }
4644

4646  @Pure
4647  public static boolean lexGTE(double @Nullable [] seq1, float @Nullable [] seq2) {
4648  if (seq1 == null) {
4649    return false;
4650  }
4651  if (seq2 == null) {
4652    return false;
4653  }
4654    int minlength = (seq1.length < seq2.length) ? seq1.length : seq2.length;
4655    for (int i = 0 ; i < minlength ; i++) {
4656      if (lt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
4657        return false;
4658      } else if (gt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
4659        return true;
4660      }
4661    }
4662    if (seq1.length < seq2.length) {
4663      return false;
4664    }
4665    return true;
4666  }

4932  /// Deferencing (accessing) fields
4933
4934  /**
4935   * collectdouble accepts an object and a list of fields (one of which is of array type, and the
4936   * rest of which are not), and produces an array in which the original object has had the given
4937   * fields accessed.
4938   *
4939   * <p>Daikon creates invariants over "variables" such as the following.
4940   *
4941   * <dl>
4942   * <dt>x.arr[].z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements y.z
4943   *              for all y's in array x.arr.</dd>
4944   * <dt>arr[].y.z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements x.y.z
4945   *              for all x's in array arr.</dd>
4946   * <dt>x.y.z[]</dt>   <dd>The result of collecting all elements in array x.y.z[]</dd>
4947   * </dl>
4948   *
4949   * <p>The collectdouble() method does this collecting work.
4950   *
4951   * <p>Given an object (x, arr, or x, correspondingly, in the above examples) and a "field string"
4952   * (arr.z, y.z, or y.z, correspondingly, in the above example), the collect method collects the
4953   * elements that result from following the fields, one of which is assumed to be an array.
4954   *
4955   * <p>
4956   * requires: fieldStr.length() &gt; 0 and object != null
4957   * <p>
4958   * requires: fieldStr contains only field names, no "[]" strings.
4959   * <p>
4960   * requires: the method only works for field sequences with exactly one field representing an
4961   * array. For example, the collection a[].b[].c will fail.
4962   *
4963   * @return if the resulting collection is of non-primitive type, then returns an array of type
4964   * Object[]. Returns null if any array or field access causes an exception.
4965   */
4966
4967  @SideEffectFree
4968  public static double @Nullable [] collectdouble(@Nullable Object object, @Nullable String fieldStr) {
4969
4970    if (object == null) {
4971      return null;
4972    }
4973    if (fieldStr == null) {
4974      return null;
4975    }
4976
4977    // assert fieldStr != null && !"".equals(fieldStr);
4978    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
4979    double[] retval = collectdouble(object, fieldNames, 0);
4980    // System.err.println("%%% fieldArray returned: " + plume.Arrays.toString(retval));
4981    return retval;
4982  }
4983
4984  /** Helper method for collectdouble(Object, String).
4985   * Operates on a subset of the fields: those in fields[fieldsStartIdx..].
4986   * @see collectdouble(Object, String)
4987   */
4988  // @PolyNull does not work for return type, because null is returned on error.
4989  @SideEffectFree
4990  private static double @Nullable [] collectdouble(@Nullable Object object,
4991                                                   String[] fields, int fieldsStartIdx) {
4992
4993    if (object == null) {
4994      return null;
4995    }
4996    assert (fields != null);
4997    assert (fieldsStartIdx >= 0 && fieldsStartIdx < fields.length);
4998
4999    Object fieldObj;
5000    try {
5001      Field field = (object instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
5002        ? ((Class<?>)object).getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx])
5003        : object.getClass().getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx]);
5004      field.setAccessible(true);
5005      // Class cls = field.getType();
5006      fieldObj = field.get(object);
5007      // System.out.println("***fieldObj="+fieldObj);
5008
5009    } catch (Exception e) {
5010      return null;
5011
5012    }
5013
5014    if (fieldObj == null) {
5015      return null;
5016    }
5017
5018    // base case: just accessed the last field
5019    if (fields.length - 1 == fieldsStartIdx) {
5020
5021      if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
5022        // last field is an array
5023        return (double[])fieldObj;
5024      } else {
5025        // This hack should be removed in favor of, at "oneEltArray = ..."
5026        // below, calling a version of collectdouble_field that throws an
5027        // error.  Then, this case becomes a run-time error.  -MDE
5028
5029        // Just one element; return a one-element array.
5030        // assert cls.equals(Double.TYPE);
5031        return new double[] { ((Double)fieldObj).doubleValue() };
5032      }
5033    } else {
5034      // recursive case: more fields to access after this one
5035
5036      if (daikon.ProglangType.list_implementors.contains(fieldObj.getClass().getName())) {
5037
5038        java.util.AbstractCollection<?> collection = (java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)fieldObj;
5039        double[] intermediate = new double[collection.size()];
5040        int index = 0;
5041        for (Iterator<?> i = collection.iterator() ; i.hasNext() ; ) {
5042          Object obj = i.next();
5043          double[] oneEltArray = collectdouble(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
5044          if (oneEltArray == null) {
5045            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
5046          }
5047          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
5048          intermediate[index++] = oneEltArray[0];
5049        }
5050        return intermediate;
5051      } else if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
5052
5053        // collect elements across array
5054        double[] intermediate = new double[Array.getLength(fieldObj)];
5055        for (int i = 0 ; i < intermediate.length ; i++) {
5056          Object obj = Array.get(fieldObj, i);
5057          double[] oneEltArray = collectdouble(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
5058          if (oneEltArray == null) {
5059            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
5060          }
5061          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
5062          intermediate[i] = oneEltArray[0];
5063        }
5064        return intermediate;
5065      } else {
5066
5067        return collectdouble(fieldObj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
5068      }
5069    }
5070  }
5071
5072  /**
5073   * Returns the results of dereferencing the fields for 'object'. For example, the call
5074   *
5075   * <pre>collectdouble_field(x, "f.g.h")</pre>
5076   *
5077   * has the same value as
5078   *
5079   * <pre>x.f.g.h</pre>.
5080   * Returns a default value if any field access causes an exception.
5081   */
5082  @SideEffectFree
5083  public static double collectdouble_field(Object object, String fieldStr) {
5084
5085    if (object == null) {
5086      return Double.NaN; // return default value
5087    }
5088    if (fieldStr == null) {
5089      return Double.NaN; // return default value
5090    }
5091
5092    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
5093
5094    // Holds the intermediate (and final) result
5095    Object fieldObj = object;
5096
5097    for (int i = 0 ; i < fieldNames.length ; i++) {
5098
5099      String fieldName = fieldNames[i];
5100
5101      try {
5102        Field field =
5103          (fieldObj instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
5104          ? ((Class<?>)fieldObj).getDeclaredField(fieldName)
5105          : fieldObj.getClass().getDeclaredField(fieldName);
5106        field.setAccessible(true);
5107        fieldObj = field.get(fieldObj);
5108
5109        if (fieldObj == null) {
5110          return Double.NaN; // return default value
5111        }
5112
5113      } catch (Exception e) {
5114        return Double.NaN; // return default value
5115
5116      }
5117
5118    }
5119
5120    return ((Double)fieldObj).doubleValue();
5121  }

5127  /**
5128   * Returns the ith element of the array or collection argument. If the argument is null or not an
5129   * array or collection, returns a default value (Float.NaN).
5130   */
5131
5132  @Pure
5133  public static float getElement_float(Object o, long i) {
5134    if (o == null) {
5135      return Float.NaN; // return default value
5136    }
5137    java.lang.Class<?> c = o.getClass();
5138    if (c.isArray()) {
5139      return java.lang.reflect.Array.getFloat(o, (int)i);
5140    } else if (o instanceof java.util.AbstractCollection<?>) {
5141      return java.lang.reflect.Array.getFloat(((java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)o).toArray(), (int)i);
5142    } else {
5143      return Float.NaN; // return default value
5144    }
5145  }
5146
5147  @Pure
5148  public static float getElement_float(float[] arr, long i) {
5149    if (arr == null) {
5150      return Float.NaN; // return default value
5151    }
5152    return arr[(int)i];
5153  }

5197  /** True iff both sequences have the same length, and all seq2[i] divide seq1[i].
5198   *
5199   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
5200   *
5201   * <pre>
5202   * /\ seq1.length == seq2.length
5203   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq2.length-1 } : seq2[i] divides seq1[i]
5204   * </pre>
5205   *
5206   */
5207  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
5208  @Pure
5209  public static boolean pairwiseDivides(float[] seq1, float[] seq2) {
5210    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
5211      return false;
5212    }
5213    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
5214    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
5215      if (ne(seq1[i] % seq2[i], 0)) {
5216        return false;
5217      }
5218    }
5219    return true;
5220  }

5278  /**
5279   * Returns the array { seq1[0], ..., seq1[seq1.length-1], seq2[0], ... , seq2[seq2.length-1] } .
5280   *
5281   * <p>If either array is null, returns null. If either array is empty, returns only those
5282   * elements in the other array. If both arrays are empty, returns a new empty array.
5283   */
5284  @SideEffectFree
5285  public static float @PolyNull [] concat(float @PolyNull [] seq1, float @PolyNull [] seq2) {
5286    if (seq1 == null) {
5287      return null;
5288    }
5289    if (seq2 == null) {
5290      return null;
5291    }
5292    return ArraysPlume.concat(seq1, seq2);
5293  }
5294
5295  @SideEffectFree
5296  public static double @PolyNull [] concat(float @PolyNull [] seq1, double @PolyNull [] seq2) {
5297    if (seq1 == null) {
5298      return null;
5299    }
5300    if (seq2 == null) {
5301      return null;
5302    }
5303    // Cannot just use ArraysPlume.concat because the two arrays
5304    // have different types.  This essentially inlines that method.
5305    int newLength = seq1.length + seq2.length;
5306    double[] retval = new double[newLength];
5307
5308    for (int j = 0 ; j < seq1.length ; j++) {
5309      retval[j] = seq1[j];
5310    }
5311    System.arraycopy(seq2, 0, retval, seq1.length, seq2.length);
5312
5313    return retval;
5314  }

5343  /**
5344   * Returns an array that is equivalent to the set intersection of seq1 and seq2. This method
5345   * gives no assurances about the order or repetition of elements: elements may be repeated, and
5346   * their order may be different from the order of elements in seq1 and seq2.
5347   */
5348  @Pure
5349  public static float @PolyNull [] intersection(float @PolyNull [] seq1, float @PolyNull [] seq2) {
5350    if (seq1 == null) {
5351      return null;
5352    }
5353    if (seq2 == null) {
5354      return null;
5355    }
5356    float[] intermediate = new float[Math.min(seq1.length, seq2.length)];
5357    int length = 0;
5358    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
5359      if (memberOf(seq1[i], seq2) ) {
5360        intermediate[length++] = seq1[i];
5361      }
5362    }
5363    return ArraysPlume.subarray(intermediate, 0, length);
5364  }

5470  /** True iff seq1 is the reverse of seq2.
5471   *
5472   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
5473   *
5474   * <pre>
5475   * /\ seq1.length == seq2.length
5476   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq1.length-1 } : seq1[i] == seq2[seq2.length-1-i]
5477   * </pre>
5478   *
5479   */
5480  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
5481  @Pure
5482  public static boolean isReverse(float[] seq1, float[] seq2) {
5483    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
5484      return false;
5485    }
5486    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
5487    int length = seq1.length;
5488    for (int i = 0 ; i < length ; i++) {
5489      if (ne(seq1[i], seq2[length - i - 1])) {
5490        return false;
5491      }
5492    }
5493    return true;
5494  }

5586  /** Returns a subsequence of seq with first elements seq[start] and last element seq[end]. */
5587  @Pure
5588  public static float @PolyNull [] slice(float @PolyNull [] seq, int start, int end) {
5589    if (seq == null) {
5590      return null;
5591    }
5592    int sliceStart = start;
5593    int sliceEnd = end;
5594    if (start < 0) {
5595      return new float[] { };
5596    }
5597    if (end > seq.length - 1) {
5598      return new float[] { };
5599    }
5600    if (sliceStart > sliceEnd) {
5601      return new float[] { };
5602    }
5603    int length = sliceEnd - sliceStart + 1;
5604    return ArraysPlume.subarray(seq, sliceStart, length);
5605  }

5843      return false;

5953   *
5954   */
5955  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
5956  @Pure
5957  public static boolean pairwiseLTE(float @Nullable [] seq1, float @Nullable [] seq2) {
5958    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
5959      return false;
5960    }
5961    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
5962    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
5963      if (gt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
5964        return false;
5965      }
5966    }
5967    return true;
5968  }

6112  /** Returns true iff seq1 is lexically &lt;  seq2. */
6113  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
6114  @Pure
6115  public static boolean lexLT(float @Nullable [] seq1, float @Nullable [] seq2) {
6116    if (seq1 == null) {
6117      return false;
6118    }
6119    if (seq2 == null) {
6120      return false;
6121    }
6122    int minlength = (seq1.length < seq2.length) ? seq1.length : seq2.length;
6123    for (int i = 0 ; i < minlength ; i++) {
6124      if (gt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
6125        return false;
6126      } else if (lt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
6127        return true;
6128      }
6129    }
6130    if (seq1.length >= seq2.length) {
6131      return false;
6132    }
6133    return true;
6134  }

6563
6564  /// Deferencing (accessing) fields
6565
6566  /**
6567   * collectfloat accepts an object and a list of fields (one of which is of array type, and the
6568   * rest of which are not), and produces an array in which the original object has had the given
6569   * fields accessed.
6570   *
6571   * <p>Daikon creates invariants over "variables" such as the following.
6572   *
6573   * <dl>
6574   * <dt>x.arr[].z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements y.z
6575   *              for all y's in array x.arr.</dd>
6576   * <dt>arr[].y.z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements x.y.z
6577   *              for all x's in array arr.</dd>
6578   * <dt>x.y.z[]</dt>   <dd>The result of collecting all elements in array x.y.z[]</dd>
6579   * </dl>
6580   *
6581   * <p>The collectfloat() method does this collecting work.
6582   *
6583   * <p>Given an object (x, arr, or x, correspondingly, in the above examples) and a "field string"
6584   * (arr.z, y.z, or y.z, correspondingly, in the above example), the collect method collects the
6585   * elements that result from following the fields, one of which is assumed to be an array.
6586   *
6587   * <p>
6588   * requires: fieldStr.length() &gt; 0 and object != null
6589   * <p>
6590   * requires: fieldStr contains only field names, no "[]" strings.
6591   * <p>
6592   * requires: the method only works for field sequences with exactly one field representing an
6593   * array. For example, the collection a[].b[].c will fail.
6594   *
6595   * @return if the resulting collection is of non-primitive type, then returns an array of type
6596   * Object[]. Returns null if any array or field access causes an exception.
6597   */
6598
6599  @SideEffectFree
6600  public static float @Nullable [] collectfloat(@Nullable Object object, @Nullable String fieldStr) {
6601
6602    if (object == null) {
6603      return null;
6604    }
6605    if (fieldStr == null) {
6606      return null;
6607    }
6608
6609    // assert fieldStr != null && !"".equals(fieldStr);
6610    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
6611    float[] retval = collectfloat(object, fieldNames, 0);
6612    // System.err.println("%%% fieldArray returned: " + plume.Arrays.toString(retval));
6613    return retval;
6614  }
6615
6616  /** Helper method for collectfloat(Object, String).
6617   * Operates on a subset of the fields: those in fields[fieldsStartIdx..].
6618   * @see collectfloat(Object, String)
6619   */
6620  // @PolyNull does not work for return type, because null is returned on error.
6621  @SideEffectFree
6622  private static float @Nullable [] collectfloat(@Nullable Object object,
6623                                                   String[] fields, int fieldsStartIdx) {
6624
6625    if (object == null) {
6626      return null;
6627    }
6628    assert (fields != null);
6629    assert (fieldsStartIdx >= 0 && fieldsStartIdx < fields.length);
6630
6631    Object fieldObj;
6632    try {
6633      Field field = (object instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
6634        ? ((Class<?>)object).getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx])
6635        : object.getClass().getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx]);
6636      field.setAccessible(true);
6637      // Class cls = field.getType();
6638      fieldObj = field.get(object);
6639      // System.out.println("***fieldObj="+fieldObj);
6640
6641    } catch (Exception e) {
6642      return null;
6643
6644    }
6645
6646    if (fieldObj == null) {
6647      return null;
6648    }
6649
6650    // base case: just accessed the last field
6651    if (fields.length - 1 == fieldsStartIdx) {
6652
6653      if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
6654        // last field is an array
6655        return (float[])fieldObj;
6656      } else {
6657        // This hack should be removed in favor of, at "oneEltArray = ..."
6658        // below, calling a version of collectfloat_field that throws an
6659        // error.  Then, this case becomes a run-time error.  -MDE
6660
6661        // Just one element; return a one-element array.
6662        // assert cls.equals(Float.TYPE);
6663        return new float[] { ((Float)fieldObj).floatValue() };
6664      }
6665    } else {
6666      // recursive case: more fields to access after this one
6667
6668      if (daikon.ProglangType.list_implementors.contains(fieldObj.getClass().getName())) {
6669
6670        java.util.AbstractCollection<?> collection = (java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)fieldObj;
6671        float[] intermediate = new float[collection.size()];
6672        int index = 0;
6673        for (Iterator<?> i = collection.iterator() ; i.hasNext() ; ) {
6674          Object obj = i.next();
6675          float[] oneEltArray = collectfloat(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
6676          if (oneEltArray == null) {
6677            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
6678          }
6679          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
6680          intermediate[index++] = oneEltArray[0];
6681        }
6682        return intermediate;
6683      } else if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
6684
6685        // collect elements across array
6686        float[] intermediate = new float[Array.getLength(fieldObj)];
6687        for (int i = 0 ; i < intermediate.length ; i++) {
6688          Object obj = Array.get(fieldObj, i);
6689          float[] oneEltArray = collectfloat(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
6690          if (oneEltArray == null) {
6691            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
6692          }
6693          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
6694          intermediate[i] = oneEltArray[0];
6695        }
6696        return intermediate;
6697      } else {
6698
6699        return collectfloat(fieldObj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
6700      }
6701    }
6702  }
6703
6704  /**
6705   * Returns the results of dereferencing the fields for 'object'. For example, the call
6706   *
6707   * <pre>collectfloat_field(x, "f.g.h")</pre>
6708   *
6709   * has the same value as
6710   *
6711   * <pre>x.f.g.h</pre>.
6712   * Returns a default value if any field access causes an exception.
6713   */
6714  @SideEffectFree
6715  public static float collectfloat_field(Object object, String fieldStr) {
6716
6717    if (object == null) {
6718      return Float.NaN; // return default value
6719    }
6720    if (fieldStr == null) {
6721      return Float.NaN; // return default value
6722    }
6723
6724    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
6725
6726    // Holds the intermediate (and final) result
6727    Object fieldObj = object;
6728
6729    for (int i = 0 ; i < fieldNames.length ; i++) {
6730
6731      String fieldName = fieldNames[i];
6732
6733      try {
6734        Field field =
6735          (fieldObj instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
6736          ? ((Class<?>)fieldObj).getDeclaredField(fieldName)
6737          : fieldObj.getClass().getDeclaredField(fieldName);
6738        field.setAccessible(true);
6739        fieldObj = field.get(fieldObj);
6740
6741        if (fieldObj == null) {
6742          return Float.NaN; // return default value
6743        }
6744
6745      } catch (Exception e) {
6746        return Float.NaN; // return default value
6747
6748      }
6749
6750    }
6751
6752    return ((Float)fieldObj).floatValue();
6753  }

6759  /**
6760   * Returns the ith element of the array or collection argument. If the argument is null or not an
6761   * array or collection, returns a default value (Integer.MAX_VALUE).
6762   */
6763
6764  @Pure
6765  public static int getElement_int(Object o, long i) {
6766    if (o == null) {
6767      return Integer.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
6768    }
6769    java.lang.Class<?> c = o.getClass();
6770    if (c.isArray()) {
6771      return java.lang.reflect.Array.getInt(o, (int)i);
6772    } else if (o instanceof java.util.AbstractCollection<?>) {
6773      return java.lang.reflect.Array.getInt(((java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)o).toArray(), (int)i);
6774    } else {
6775      return Integer.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
6776    }
6777  }
6778
6779  @Pure
6780  public static int getElement_int(int[] arr, long i) {
6781    if (arr == null) {
6782      return Integer.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
6783    }
6784    return arr[(int)i];
6785  }

6829  /** True iff both sequences have the same length, and all seq2[i] divide seq1[i].
6830   *
6831   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
6832   *
6833   * <pre>
6834   * /\ seq1.length == seq2.length
6835   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq2.length-1 } : seq2[i] divides seq1[i]
6836   * </pre>
6837   *
6838   */
6839  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
6840  @Pure
6841  public static boolean pairwiseDivides(int[] seq1, int[] seq2) {
6842    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
6843      return false;
6844    }
6845    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
6846    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
6847      if (ne(seq1[i] % seq2[i], 0)) {
6848        return false;
6849      }
6850    }
6851    return true;
6852  }

6980   * </pre>
6981   *
6982   */
6983  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
6984  @Pure

6986    if (seq1 == null) {

6990      return false;
6991    }
6992    if (seq1.length != seq2.length) {
6993      return false;

6996      if (ne(seq1[i], (seq2[i] | seq1[i]))) {
6997        return false;
6998      }
6999    }
7000    return true;

7041  /**
7042   * Returns the array { seq1[0], ..., seq1[seq1.length-1], seq2[0], ... , seq2[seq2.length-1] } .
7043   *
7044   * <p>If either array is null, returns null. If either array is empty, returns only those
7045   * elements in the other array. If both arrays are empty, returns a new empty array.
7046   */
7047  @SideEffectFree
7048  public static int @PolyNull [] concat(int @PolyNull [] seq1, int @PolyNull [] seq2) {
7049    if (seq1 == null) {
7050      return null;
7051    }
7052    if (seq2 == null) {
7053      return null;
7054    }
7055    return ArraysPlume.concat(seq1, seq2);
7056  }

7058  @SideEffectFree
7059  public static long @PolyNull [] concat(int @PolyNull [] seq1, long @PolyNull [] seq2) {
7060    if (seq1 == null) {
7061      return null;
7062    }
7063    if (seq2 == null) {
7064      return null;
7065    }
7066    // Cannot just use ArraysPlume.concat because the two arrays
7067    // have different types.  This essentially inlines that method.
7068    int newLength = seq1.length + seq2.length;
7069    long[] retval = new long[newLength];
7070
7071    for (int j = 0 ; j < seq1.length ; j++) {
7072      retval[j] = seq1[j];
7073    }
7074    System.arraycopy(seq2, 0, retval, seq1.length, seq2.length);
7075
7076    return retval;
7077  }

7106  /**
7107   * Returns an array that is equivalent to the set intersection of seq1 and seq2. This method
7108   * gives no assurances about the order or repetition of elements: elements may be repeated, and
7109   * their order may be different from the order of elements in seq1 and seq2.
7110   */
7111  @Pure
7112  public static int @PolyNull [] intersection(int @PolyNull [] seq1, int @PolyNull [] seq2) {
7113    if (seq1 == null) {
7114      return null;
7115    }
7116    if (seq2 == null) {
7117      return null;
7118    }
7119    int[] intermediate = new int[Math.min(seq1.length, seq2.length)];
7120    int length = 0;
7121    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
7122      if (memberOf(seq1[i], seq2) ) {
7123        intermediate[length++] = seq1[i];
7124      }
7125    }
7126    return ArraysPlume.subarray(intermediate, 0, length);
7127  }

7233  /** True iff seq1 is the reverse of seq2.
7234   *
7235   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
7236   *
7237   * <pre>
7238   * /\ seq1.length == seq2.length
7239   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq1.length-1 } : seq1[i] == seq2[seq2.length-1-i]
7240   * </pre>
7241   *
7242   */
7243  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
7244  @Pure
7245  public static boolean isReverse(int[] seq1, int[] seq2) {
7246    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
7247      return false;
7248    }
7249    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
7250    int length = seq1.length;
7251    for (int i = 0 ; i < length ; i++) {
7252      if (ne(seq1[i], seq2[length - i - 1])) {
7253        return false;
7254      }
7255    }
7256    return true;
7257  }
7258
7259  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
7260  @Pure
7261  public static boolean isReverse(int @Nullable [] seq1, long @Nullable [] seq2) {
7262    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
7263      return false;
7264    }
7265    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
7266    int length = seq1.length;
7267    for (int i = 0 ; i < length ; i++) {
7268      if (ne(seq1[i], seq2[length - i - 1])) {
7269        return false;
7270      }
7271    }
7272    return true;
7273  }
7274
7275  /** True iff all elements in elts occur once or more in arr;
7276   * that is, elts is a subset of arr.
7277   *
7278   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
7279   *
7280   * forall i in { 0..elt.length-1 } : elt[i] element_of arr
7281   *
7282   */
7283  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
7284  @Pure
7285  public static boolean subsetOf(@Nullable Object elts, @Nullable Object arr) {
7286    if (elts == null) {
7287      return false;
7288    }
7289    if (arr == null) {
7290      return false;
7291    }
7292    if (!(elts.getClass().isArray() && arr.getClass().isArray())) {
7293      // throw new IllegalArgumentException("both arguments must be arrays.");
7294      return false;
7295    }
7296    // We know that the two arguments are arrays of different types; if
7297    // they had been of the same type, then one of the more specific
7298    // overriding versions of this method would have been called.
7299
7300    // This implementation simply calls either subsetOf(long[], long[]) or
7301    // subsetOf(double[], double[]).
7302
7303    Class<?> eltsType = elts.getClass().getComponentType();
7304    Class<?> arrType = arr.getClass().getComponentType();
7305    if (isIntegralType(eltsType) && isIntegralType(arrType)) {
7306      // Both arrays are int/long.
7307      // Cast both arrays to long and call subsetOf(long[],long[]).
7308      long[] elts_long;
7309      if (eltsType == Long.class) {
7310        elts_long = (long[]) elts;
7311      } else {
7312        elts_long = new long[Array.getLength(elts)];
7313        for (int i = 0 ; i < elts_long.length ; i++) {
7314          elts_long[i] = Array.getLong(elts, i);
7315        }
7316      }
7317      long[] arr_long;
7318      if (arrType == Long.class) {
7319        arr_long = (long[]) arr;
7320      } else {
7321        arr_long = new long[Array.getLength(arr)];
7322        for (int i = 0 ; i < arr_long.length ; i++) {
7323          arr_long[i] = Array.getLong(arr, i);
7324        }
7325      }
7326      return subsetOf(elts_long, arr_long);
7327    } else if (isNumericType(eltsType) && isNumericType(arrType)) {
7328      // At least one array is float/double.
7329      // Cast both arrays to double and call subsetOf(double[],double[])
7330      double[] elts_double = new double[Array.getLength(elts)];
7331      for (int i = 0 ; i < elts_double.length ; i++) {
7332        elts_double[i] = Array.getDouble(elts, i);
7333      }
7334      double[] arr_double = new double[Array.getLength(arr)];
7335      for (int i = 0 ; i < arr_double.length ; i++) {
7336        arr_double[i] = Array.getDouble(arr, i);
7337      }
7338      return subsetOf(elts_double, arr_double);
7339    } else {
7340      // throw new IllegalArgumentException("both arguments must be arrays of numeric types.");
7341      return false;
7342    }
7343
7344  }
7345
7346  /** True iff seq1 is a subset of seq2, when the sequences are considered as sets. */
7347  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
7348  @Pure
7349  public static boolean subsetOf(int @Nullable [] seq1, int @Nullable [] seq2) {
7350    if (seq1 == null) {
7351      return false;
7352    }
7353    if (seq2 == null) {
7354      return false;
7355    }
7356    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
7357      if (!memberOf(seq1[i], seq2)) {
7358        return false;
7359      }
7360    }
7361    return true;
7362  }
7363
7364  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
7365  @Pure
7366  public static boolean subsetOf(int @Nullable [] seq1, long @Nullable [] seq2) {
7367    if (seq1 == null) {
7368      return false;
7369    }
7370    if (seq2 == null) {
7371      return false;
7372    }
7373    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
7374      if (!memberOf(seq1[i], seq2)) {
7375        return false;
7376      }
7377    }
7378    return true;
7379  }

7420  /** Returns a subsequence of seq with first elements seq[start] and last element seq[end]. */
7421  @Pure
7422  public static int @PolyNull [] slice(int @PolyNull [] seq, int start, int end) {
7423    if (seq == null) {
7424      return null;
7425    }
7426    int sliceStart = start;
7427    int sliceEnd = end;
7428    if (start < 0) {
7429      return new int[] { };
7430    }
7431    if (end > seq.length - 1) {
7432      return new int[] { };
7433    }
7434    if (sliceStart > sliceEnd) {
7435      return new int[] { };
7436    }
7437    int length = sliceEnd - sliceStart + 1;
7438    return ArraysPlume.subarray(seq, sliceStart, length);
7439  }
7440
7441  @Pure
7442  public static int @PolyNull [] slice(int @PolyNull [] seq, long start, int end) {
7443    return slice(seq, (int)start, end);
7444  }
7445  @Pure
7446  public static int @PolyNull [] slice(int @PolyNull [] seq, int start, long end) {
7447    return slice(seq, start, (int)end);
7448  }
7449  @Pure
7450  public static int @PolyNull [] slice(int @PolyNull [] seq, long start, long end) {
7451    return slice(seq, (int)start, (int)end);
7452  }

7892   * For equality, "lexically" and "pairwise" are the same.
7893   */
7894  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})

7897    if (seq1 == null) {
7898      return false;
7899    }
7900    if (seq2 == null) {
7901      return false;
7902    }
7903    return pairwiseEqual(seq1, seq2);
7904  }

7943  /** Returns true iff seq1 is lexically &lt;  seq2. */
7944  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
7945  @Pure
7946  public static boolean lexLT(int @Nullable [] seq1, int @Nullable [] seq2) {
7947    if (seq1 == null) {
7948      return false;
7949    }
7950    if (seq2 == null) {
7951      return false;
7952    }
7953    int minlength = (seq1.length < seq2.length) ? seq1.length : seq2.length;
7954    for (int i = 0 ; i < minlength ; i++) {
7955      if (gt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
7956        return false;
7957      } else if (lt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
7958        return true;
7959      }
7960    }
7961    if (seq1.length >= seq2.length) {
7962      return false;
7963    }
7964    return true;
7965  }

8131  /** True iff for all applicable i, every seq[i] == seq[i+1].
8132   *
8133   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
8134   *
8135   * forall i in { 0..seq.length-2 } : seq[i] == seq[i+1]
8136   *
8137   */
8138  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression="#1")
8139  @Pure
8140  public static boolean eltwiseEqual(int @Nullable [] seq) {
8141  if (seq == null) {
8142    return false;
8143  }
8144    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq.length ; i++) {
8145      if (i < seq.length - 1) {
8146        if (ne(seq[i], seq[i + 1])) {
8147          return false;
8148        }
8149      }
8150    }
8151    return true;
8152  }
