8394
8395  /// Deferencing (accessing) fields
8396
8397  /**
8398   * collectint accepts an object and a list of fields (one of which is of array type, and the
8399   * rest of which are not), and produces an array in which the original object has had the given
8400   * fields accessed.
8401   *
8402   * <p>Daikon creates invariants over "variables" such as the following.
8403   *
8404   * <dl>
8405   * <dt>x.arr[].z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements y.z
8406   *              for all y's in array x.arr.</dd>
8407   * <dt>arr[].y.z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements x.y.z
8408   *              for all x's in array arr.</dd>
8409   * <dt>x.y.z[]</dt>   <dd>The result of collecting all elements in array x.y.z[]</dd>
8410   * </dl>
8411   *
8412   * <p>The collectint() method does this collecting work.
8413   *
8414   * <p>Given an object (x, arr, or x, correspondingly, in the above examples) and a "field string"
8415   * (arr.z, y.z, or y.z, correspondingly, in the above example), the collect method collects the
8416   * elements that result from following the fields, one of which is assumed to be an array.
8417   *
8418   * <p>
8419   * requires: fieldStr.length() &gt; 0 and object != null
8420   * <p>
8421   * requires: fieldStr contains only field names, no "[]" strings.
8422   * <p>
8423   * requires: the method only works for field sequences with exactly one field representing an
8424   * array. For example, the collection a[].b[].c will fail.
8425   *
8426   * @return if the resulting collection is of non-primitive type, then returns an array of type
8427   * Object[]. Returns null if any array or field access causes an exception.
8428   */
8429
8430  @SideEffectFree
8431  public static int @Nullable [] collectint(@Nullable Object object, @Nullable String fieldStr) {
8432
8433    if (object == null) {
8434      return null;
8435    }
8436    if (fieldStr == null) {
8437      return null;
8438    }
8439
8440    // assert fieldStr != null && !"".equals(fieldStr);
8441    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
8442    int[] retval = collectint(object, fieldNames, 0);
8443    // System.err.println("%%% fieldArray returned: " + plume.Arrays.toString(retval));
8444    return retval;
8445  }
8446
8447  /** Helper method for collectint(Object, String).
8448   * Operates on a subset of the fields: those in fields[fieldsStartIdx..].
8449   * @see collectint(Object, String)
8450   */
8451  // @PolyNull does not work for return type, because null is returned on error.
8452  @SideEffectFree
8453  private static int @Nullable [] collectint(@Nullable Object object,
8454                                                   String[] fields, int fieldsStartIdx) {
8455
8456    if (object == null) {
8457      return null;
8458    }
8459    assert (fields != null);
8460    assert (fieldsStartIdx >= 0 && fieldsStartIdx < fields.length);
8461
8462    Object fieldObj;
8463    try {
8464      Field field = (object instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
8465        ? ((Class<?>)object).getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx])
8466        : object.getClass().getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx]);
8467      field.setAccessible(true);
8468      // Class cls = field.getType();
8469      fieldObj = field.get(object);
8470      // System.out.println("***fieldObj="+fieldObj);
8471
8472    } catch (Exception e) {
8473      return null;
8474
8475    }
8476
8477    if (fieldObj == null) {
8478      return null;
8479    }
8480
8481    // base case: just accessed the last field
8482    if (fields.length - 1 == fieldsStartIdx) {
8483
8484      if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
8485        // last field is an array
8486        return (int[])fieldObj;
8487      } else {
8488        // This hack should be removed in favor of, at "oneEltArray = ..."
8489        // below, calling a version of collectint_field that throws an
8490        // error.  Then, this case becomes a run-time error.  -MDE
8491
8492        // Just one element; return a one-element array.
8493        // assert cls.equals(Integer.TYPE);
8494        return new int[] { ((Integer)fieldObj).intValue() };
8495      }
8496    } else {
8497      // recursive case: more fields to access after this one
8498
8499      if (daikon.ProglangType.list_implementors.contains(fieldObj.getClass().getName())) {
8500
8501        java.util.AbstractCollection<?> collection = (java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)fieldObj;
8502        int[] intermediate = new int[collection.size()];
8503        int index = 0;
8504        for (Iterator<?> i = collection.iterator() ; i.hasNext() ; ) {
8505          Object obj = i.next();
8506          int[] oneEltArray = collectint(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
8507          if (oneEltArray == null) {
8508            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
8509          }
8510          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
8511          intermediate[index++] = oneEltArray[0];
8512        }
8513        return intermediate;
8514      } else if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
8515
8516        // collect elements across array
8517        int[] intermediate = new int[Array.getLength(fieldObj)];
8518        for (int i = 0 ; i < intermediate.length ; i++) {
8519          Object obj = Array.get(fieldObj, i);
8520          int[] oneEltArray = collectint(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
8521          if (oneEltArray == null) {
8522            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
8523          }
8524          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
8525          intermediate[i] = oneEltArray[0];
8526        }
8527        return intermediate;
8528      } else {
8529
8530        return collectint(fieldObj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
8531      }
8532    }
8533  }
8534
8535  /**
8536   * Returns the results of dereferencing the fields for 'object'. For example, the call
8537   *
8538   * <pre>collectint_field(x, "f.g.h")</pre>
8539   *
8540   * has the same value as
8541   *
8542   * <pre>x.f.g.h</pre>.
8543   * Returns a default value if any field access causes an exception.
8544   */
8545  @SideEffectFree
8546  public static int collectint_field(Object object, String fieldStr) {
8547
8548    if (object == null) {
8549      return Integer.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
8550    }
8551    if (fieldStr == null) {
8552      return Integer.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
8553    }
8554
8555    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
8556
8557    // Holds the intermediate (and final) result
8558    Object fieldObj = object;
8559
8560    for (int i = 0 ; i < fieldNames.length ; i++) {
8561
8562      String fieldName = fieldNames[i];
8563
8564      try {
8565        Field field =
8566          (fieldObj instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
8567          ? ((Class<?>)fieldObj).getDeclaredField(fieldName)
8568          : fieldObj.getClass().getDeclaredField(fieldName);
8569        field.setAccessible(true);
8570        fieldObj = field.get(fieldObj);
8571
8572        if (fieldObj == null) {
8573          return Integer.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
8574        }
8575
8576      } catch (Exception e) {
8577        return Integer.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
8578
8579      }
8580
8581    }
8582
8583    return ((Integer)fieldObj).intValue();
8584  }

8590  /**
8591   * Returns the ith element of the array or collection argument. If the argument is null or not an
8592   * array or collection, returns a default value (Long.MAX_VALUE).
8593   */
8594
8595  @Pure
8596  public static long getElement_long(Object o, long i) {
8597    if (o == null) {
8598      return Long.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
8599    }
8600    java.lang.Class<?> c = o.getClass();
8601    if (c.isArray()) {
8602      return java.lang.reflect.Array.getLong(o, (int)i);
8603    } else if (o instanceof java.util.AbstractCollection<?>) {
8604      return java.lang.reflect.Array.getLong(((java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)o).toArray(), (int)i);
8605    } else {
8606      return Long.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
8607    }
8608  }

8614    }
8615    return arr[(int)i];
8616  }

8824  /**

8826   *
8827   * <p>If either array is null, returns null. If either array is empty, returns only those
8828   * elements in the other array. If both arrays are empty, returns a new empty array.
8829   */
8830  @SideEffectFree
8831  public static long @PolyNull [] concat(long @PolyNull [] seq1, long @PolyNull [] seq2) {
8832    if (seq1 == null) {
8833      return null;
8834    }
8835    if (seq2 == null) {
8836      return null;
8837    }

8839  }
8840
8841  @SideEffectFree
8842  public static long @PolyNull [] concat(long @PolyNull [] seq1, int @PolyNull [] seq2) {
8843    if (seq1 == null) {
8844      return null;
8845    }
8846    if (seq2 == null) {
8847      return null;
8848    }
8849    // Cannot just use ArraysPlume.concat because the two arrays
8850    // have different types.  This essentially inlines that method.
8851    int newLength = seq1.length + seq2.length;
8852    long[] retval = new long[newLength];
8853
8854    System.arraycopy(seq1, 0, retval, 0, seq1.length);
8855    for (int j = 0 ; j < seq2.length ; j++) {
8856      retval[seq1.length + j] = seq2[j];
8857    }
8858
8859    return retval;
8860  }

8893   */
8894  @Pure
8895  public static long @PolyNull [] intersection(long @PolyNull [] seq1, long @PolyNull [] seq2) {
8896    if (seq1 == null) {
8897      return null;
8898    }
8899    if (seq2 == null) {
8900      return null;
8901    }
8902    long[] intermediate = new long[Math.min(seq1.length, seq2.length)];
8903    int length = 0;
8904    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
8905      if (memberOf(seq1[i], seq2) ) {
8906        intermediate[length++] = seq1[i];
8907      }
8908    }
8909    return ArraysPlume.subarray(intermediate, 0, length);
8910  }

9132  /** Returns a subsequence of seq with first elements seq[start] and last element seq[end]. */
9133  @Pure
9134  public static long @PolyNull [] slice(long @PolyNull [] seq, int start, int end) {
9135    if (seq == null) {
9136      return null;
9137    }
9138    int sliceStart = start;
9139    int sliceEnd = end;
9140    if (start < 0) {
9141      return new long[] { };
9142    }
9143    if (end > seq.length - 1) {
9144      return new long[] { };
9145    }
9146    if (sliceStart > sliceEnd) {
9147      return new long[] { };
9148    }
9149    int length = sliceEnd - sliceStart + 1;
9150    return ArraysPlume.subarray(seq, sliceStart, length);
9151  }

9376  /** True iff seq1 and seq2 have the same length, and every seq1[i] == seq2[i].
9377   *

9379   *
9380   * /\ seq1.length == se2.length
9381   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq1.length-1 } : seq1[i] == seq2[i]
9382   *
9383   */
9384
9385  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
9386  @Pure
9387  public static boolean pairwiseEqual(long @Nullable [] seq1, long @Nullable [] seq2) {
9388    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
9389      return false;
9390    }
9391    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
9392    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
9393      if (ne(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
9394        return false;
9395      }
9396    }
9397    return true;
9398  }

9655  /** Returns true iff seq1 is lexically &lt;  seq2. */
9656  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
9657  @Pure
9658  public static boolean lexLT(long @Nullable [] seq1, long @Nullable [] seq2) {
9659    if (seq1 == null) {
9660      return false;
9661    }
9662    if (seq2 == null) {
9663      return false;
9664    }
9665    int minlength = (seq1.length < seq2.length) ? seq1.length : seq2.length;
9666    for (int i = 0 ; i < minlength ; i++) {
9667      if (gt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
9668        return false;
9669      } else if (lt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
9670        return true;
9671      }
9672    }
9673    if (seq1.length >= seq2.length) {
9674      return false;
9675    }
9676    return true;
9677  }

9843  /** True iff for all applicable i, every seq[i] == seq[i+1].
9844   *
9845   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
9846   *
9847   * forall i in { 0..seq.length-2 } : seq[i] == seq[i+1]
9848   *

9851  @Pure
9852  public static boolean eltwiseEqual(long @Nullable [] seq) {

9854    return false;

9856    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq.length ; i++) {
9857      if (i < seq.length - 1) {
9858        if (ne(seq[i], seq[i + 1])) {
9859          return false;
9860        }
9861      }
9862    }
9863    return true;
9864  }

10107  /// Deferencing (accessing) fields
10108
10109  /**
10110   * collectlong accepts an object and a list of fields (one of which is of array type, and the
10111   * rest of which are not), and produces an array in which the original object has had the given
10112   * fields accessed.
10113   *
10114   * <p>Daikon creates invariants over "variables" such as the following.
10115   *
10116   * <dl>
10117   * <dt>x.arr[].z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements y.z
10118   *              for all y's in array x.arr.</dd>
10119   * <dt>arr[].y.z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements x.y.z
10120   *              for all x's in array arr.</dd>
10121   * <dt>x.y.z[]</dt>   <dd>The result of collecting all elements in array x.y.z[]</dd>
10122   * </dl>
10123   *
10124   * <p>The collectlong() method does this collecting work.
10125   *
10126   * <p>Given an object (x, arr, or x, correspondingly, in the above examples) and a "field string"
10127   * (arr.z, y.z, or y.z, correspondingly, in the above example), the collect method collects the
10128   * elements that result from following the fields, one of which is assumed to be an array.
10129   *
10130   * <p>
10131   * requires: fieldStr.length() &gt; 0 and object != null
10132   * <p>
10133   * requires: fieldStr contains only field names, no "[]" strings.
10134   * <p>
10135   * requires: the method only works for field sequences with exactly one field representing an
10136   * array. For example, the collection a[].b[].c will fail.
10137   *
10138   * @return if the resulting collection is of non-primitive type, then returns an array of type
10139   * Object[]. Returns null if any array or field access causes an exception.
10140   */
10141
10142  @SideEffectFree
10143  public static long @Nullable [] collectlong(@Nullable Object object, @Nullable String fieldStr) {
10144
10145    if (object == null) {
10146      return null;
10147    }
10148    if (fieldStr == null) {
10149      return null;
10150    }
10151
10152    // assert fieldStr != null && !"".equals(fieldStr);
10153    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
10154    long[] retval = collectlong(object, fieldNames, 0);
10155    // System.err.println("%%% fieldArray returned: " + plume.Arrays.toString(retval));
10156    return retval;
10157  }
10158
10159  /** Helper method for collectlong(Object, String).
10160   * Operates on a subset of the fields: those in fields[fieldsStartIdx..].
10161   * @see collectlong(Object, String)
10162   */
10163  // @PolyNull does not work for return type, because null is returned on error.
10164  @SideEffectFree
10165  private static long @Nullable [] collectlong(@Nullable Object object,
10166                                                   String[] fields, int fieldsStartIdx) {
10167
10168    if (object == null) {
10169      return null;
10170    }
10171    assert (fields != null);
10172    assert (fieldsStartIdx >= 0 && fieldsStartIdx < fields.length);
10173
10174    Object fieldObj;
10175    try {
10176      Field field = (object instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
10177        ? ((Class<?>)object).getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx])
10178        : object.getClass().getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx]);
10179      field.setAccessible(true);
10180      // Class cls = field.getType();
10181      fieldObj = field.get(object);
10182      // System.out.println("***fieldObj="+fieldObj);
10183
10184    } catch (Exception e) {
10185      return null;
10186
10187    }
10188
10189    if (fieldObj == null) {
10190      return null;
10191    }
10192
10193    // base case: just accessed the last field
10194    if (fields.length - 1 == fieldsStartIdx) {
10195
10196      if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
10197        // last field is an array
10198        return (long[])fieldObj;
10199      } else {
10200        // This hack should be removed in favor of, at "oneEltArray = ..."
10201        // below, calling a version of collectlong_field that throws an
10202        // error.  Then, this case becomes a run-time error.  -MDE
10203
10204        // Just one element; return a one-element array.
10205        // assert cls.equals(Long.TYPE);
10206        return new long[] { ((Long)fieldObj).longValue() };
10207      }
10208    } else {
10209      // recursive case: more fields to access after this one
10210
10211      if (daikon.ProglangType.list_implementors.contains(fieldObj.getClass().getName())) {
10212
10213        java.util.AbstractCollection<?> collection = (java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)fieldObj;
10214        long[] intermediate = new long[collection.size()];
10215        int index = 0;
10216        for (Iterator<?> i = collection.iterator() ; i.hasNext() ; ) {
10217          Object obj = i.next();
10218          long[] oneEltArray = collectlong(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
10219          if (oneEltArray == null) {
10220            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
10221          }
10222          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
10223          intermediate[index++] = oneEltArray[0];
10224        }
10225        return intermediate;
10226      } else if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
10227
10228        // collect elements across array
10229        long[] intermediate = new long[Array.getLength(fieldObj)];
10230        for (int i = 0 ; i < intermediate.length ; i++) {
10231          Object obj = Array.get(fieldObj, i);
10232          long[] oneEltArray = collectlong(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
10233          if (oneEltArray == null) {
10234            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
10235          }
10236          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
10237          intermediate[i] = oneEltArray[0];
10238        }
10239        return intermediate;
10240      } else {
10241
10242        return collectlong(fieldObj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
10243      }
10244    }
10245  }
10246
10247  /**
10248   * Returns the results of dereferencing the fields for 'object'. For example, the call
10249   *
10250   * <pre>collectlong_field(x, "f.g.h")</pre>
10251   *
10252   * has the same value as
10253   *
10254   * <pre>x.f.g.h</pre>.
10255   * Returns a default value if any field access causes an exception.
10256   */
10257  @SideEffectFree
10258  public static long collectlong_field(Object object, String fieldStr) {
10259
10260    if (object == null) {
10261      return Long.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
10262    }
10263    if (fieldStr == null) {
10264      return Long.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
10265    }
10266
10267    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
10268
10269    // Holds the intermediate (and final) result
10270    Object fieldObj = object;
10271
10272    for (int i = 0 ; i < fieldNames.length ; i++) {
10273
10274      String fieldName = fieldNames[i];
10275
10276      try {
10277        Field field =
10278          (fieldObj instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
10279          ? ((Class<?>)fieldObj).getDeclaredField(fieldName)
10280          : fieldObj.getClass().getDeclaredField(fieldName);
10281        field.setAccessible(true);
10282        fieldObj = field.get(fieldObj);
10283
10284        if (fieldObj == null) {
10285          return Long.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
10286        }
10287
10288      } catch (Exception e) {
10289        return Long.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
10290
10291      }
10292
10293    }
10294
10295    return ((Long)fieldObj).longValue();
10296  }

10302  /**
10303   * Returns the ith element of the array or collection argument. If the argument is null or not an
10304   * array or collection, returns a default value (Short.MAX_VALUE).
10305   */
10306
10307  @Pure
10308  public static short getElement_short(Object o, long i) {
10309    if (o == null) {
10310      return Short.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
10311    }
10312    java.lang.Class<?> c = o.getClass();
10313    if (c.isArray()) {
10314      return java.lang.reflect.Array.getShort(o, (int)i);
10315    } else if (o instanceof java.util.AbstractCollection<?>) {
10316      return java.lang.reflect.Array.getShort(((java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)o).toArray(), (int)i);
10317    } else {
10318      return Short.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
10319    }
10320  }
10321
10322  @Pure
10323  public static short getElement_short(short[] arr, long i) {
10324    if (arr == null) {
10325      return Short.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
10326    }
10327    return arr[(int)i];
10328  }

10396  /**
10397   * Returns an array that is equivalent to the set intersection of seq1 and seq2. This method
10398   * gives no assurances about the order or repetition of elements: elements may be repeated, and
10399   * their order may be different from the order of elements in seq1 and seq2.
10400   */
10401  @Pure
10402  public static short @PolyNull [] intersection(short @PolyNull [] seq1, short @PolyNull [] seq2) {
10403    if (seq1 == null) {
10404      return null;
10405    }
10406    if (seq2 == null) {
10407      return null;
10408    }
10409    short[] intermediate = new short[Math.min(seq1.length, seq2.length)];
10410    int length = 0;
10411    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
10412      if (memberOf(seq1[i], seq2) ) {
10413        intermediate[length++] = seq1[i];
10414      }
10415    }
10416    return ArraysPlume.subarray(intermediate, 0, length);
10417  }

10419  /**
10420   * Returns an array that is equivalent to the set difference of seq1 and seq2. This method gives
10421   * no assurances about the order or repetition of elements: elements may be repeated, and their
10422   * order may be different from the order of elements in seq1 and seq2.
10423   */
10424  @Pure
10425  public static short @PolyNull [] setDiff(short @PolyNull [] seq1, short @PolyNull [] seq2) {
10426    if (seq1 == null) {
10427      return null;
10428    }
10429    if (seq2 == null) {
10430      return null;
10431    }
10432    short[] intermediate = new short[seq1.length];
10433    int length = 0;
10434    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
10435      if (!memberOf(seq1[i], seq2)) {
10436        intermediate[length++] = seq1[i];
10437      }
10438    }
10439    return ArraysPlume.subarray(intermediate, 0, length);
10440  }

10442  /** Returns true iff seq1 and seq2 are equal when considered as sets. */
10443  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
10444  @Pure
10445  public static boolean setEqual(short @Nullable [] seq1, short @Nullable [] seq2) {
10446    if (seq1 == null) {
10447      return false;
10448    }
10449    if (seq2 == null) {
10450      return false;
10451    }
10452    for (int i = 0; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
10453      if (!memberOf(seq1[i], seq2) ) {
10454        return false;
10455      }
10456    }
10457    for (int i = 0; i < seq2.length ; i++) {
10458      if (!memberOf(seq2[i], seq1) ) {
10459        return false;
10460      }
10461    }
10462    return true;
10463  }

10465  /** True iff seq1 is the reverse of seq2.
10466   *
10467   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
10468   *
10469   * <pre>
10470   * /\ seq1.length == seq2.length
10471   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq1.length-1 } : seq1[i] == seq2[seq2.length-1-i]
10472   * </pre>
10473   *
10474   */
10475  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
10476  @Pure
10477  public static boolean isReverse(short[] seq1, short[] seq2) {
10478    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
10479      return false;
10480    }
10481    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
10482    int length = seq1.length;
10483    for (int i = 0 ; i < length ; i++) {
10484      if (ne(seq1[i], seq2[length - i - 1])) {
10485        return false;
10486      }
10487    }
10488    return true;
10489  }

10496      return false;
10497    }
10498    if (seq2 == null) {
10499      return false;
10500    }
10501    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
10502      if (!memberOf(seq1[i], seq2)) {
10503        return false;
10504      }
10505    }
10506    return true;
10507  }

10509  /** Returns true iff seq contains no duplicate elements. */
10510  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression="#1")
10511  @Pure
10512  public static boolean noDups(short @Nullable [] seq) {
10513    if (seq == null) {
10514      return false;
10515    }
10516    return ArraysPlume.noDuplicates(seq);
10517  }

10548  /** Returns a subsequence of seq with first elements seq[start] and last element seq[end]. */
10549  @Pure
10550  public static short @PolyNull [] slice(short @PolyNull [] seq, int start, int end) {
10551    if (seq == null) {
10552      return null;
10553    }
10554    int sliceStart = start;
10555    int sliceEnd = end;
10556    if (start < 0) {
10557      return new short[] { };
10558    }
10559    if (end > seq.length - 1) {
10560      return new short[] { };
10561    }
10562    if (sliceStart > sliceEnd) {
10563      return new short[] { };
10564    }
10565    int length = sliceEnd - sliceStart + 1;
10566    return ArraysPlume.subarray(seq, sliceStart, length);
10567  }
10568
10569  @Pure
10570  public static short @PolyNull [] slice(short @PolyNull [] seq, long start, int end) {
10571    return slice(seq, (int)start, end);
10572  }
10573  @Pure
10574  public static short @PolyNull [] slice(short @PolyNull [] seq, int start, long end) {
10575    return slice(seq, start, (int)end);
10576  }
10577  @Pure
10578  public static short @PolyNull [] slice(short @PolyNull [] seq, long start, long end) {
10579    return slice(seq, (int)start, (int)end);
10580  }

10708  /** True iff seq1 and seq2 have the same length, and every seq1[i] == seq2[i].
10709   *
10710   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
10711   *
10712   * /\ seq1.length == se2.length
10713   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq1.length-1 } : seq1[i] == seq2[i]
10714   *
10715   */
10716
10717  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
10718  @Pure
10719  public static boolean pairwiseEqual(short @Nullable [] seq1, short @Nullable [] seq2) {
10720    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
10721      return false;
10722    }
10723    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
10724    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
10725      if (ne(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
10726        return false;
10727      }
10728    }
10729    return true;
10730  }

10873  /** Returns true iff seq1 is lexically &lt;  seq2. */
10874  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
10875  @Pure
10876  public static boolean lexLT(short @Nullable [] seq1, short @Nullable [] seq2) {
10877    if (seq1 == null) {
10878      return false;
10879    }
10880    if (seq2 == null) {
10881      return false;
10882    }
10883    int minlength = (seq1.length < seq2.length) ? seq1.length : seq2.length;
10884    for (int i = 0 ; i < minlength ; i++) {
10885      if (gt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
10886        return false;
10887      } else if (lt(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
10888        return true;
10889      }
10890    }
10891    if (seq1.length >= seq2.length) {
10892      return false;
10893    }
10894    return true;
10895  }

11233  /// Deferencing (accessing) fields
11234
11235  /**
11236   * collectshort accepts an object and a list of fields (one of which is of array type, and the
11237   * rest of which are not), and produces an array in which the original object has had the given
11238   * fields accessed.
11239   *
11240   * <p>Daikon creates invariants over "variables" such as the following.
11241   *
11242   * <dl>
11243   * <dt>x.arr[].z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements y.z
11244   *              for all y's in array x.arr.</dd>
11245   * <dt>arr[].y.z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements x.y.z
11246   *              for all x's in array arr.</dd>
11247   * <dt>x.y.z[]</dt>   <dd>The result of collecting all elements in array x.y.z[]</dd>
11248   * </dl>
11249   *
11250   * <p>The collectshort() method does this collecting work.
11251   *
11252   * <p>Given an object (x, arr, or x, correspondingly, in the above examples) and a "field string"
11253   * (arr.z, y.z, or y.z, correspondingly, in the above example), the collect method collects the
11254   * elements that result from following the fields, one of which is assumed to be an array.
11255   *
11256   * <p>
11257   * requires: fieldStr.length() &gt; 0 and object != null
11258   * <p>
11259   * requires: fieldStr contains only field names, no "[]" strings.
11260   * <p>
11261   * requires: the method only works for field sequences with exactly one field representing an
11262   * array. For example, the collection a[].b[].c will fail.
11263   *
11264   * @return if the resulting collection is of non-primitive type, then returns an array of type
11265   * Object[]. Returns null if any array or field access causes an exception.
11266   */
11267
11268  @SideEffectFree
11269  public static short @Nullable [] collectshort(@Nullable Object object, @Nullable String fieldStr) {
11270
11271    if (object == null) {
11272      return null;
11273    }
11274    if (fieldStr == null) {
11275      return null;
11276    }
11277
11278    // assert fieldStr != null && !"".equals(fieldStr);
11279    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
11280    short[] retval = collectshort(object, fieldNames, 0);
11281    // System.err.println("%%% fieldArray returned: " + plume.Arrays.toString(retval));
11282    return retval;
11283  }
11284
11285  /** Helper method for collectshort(Object, String).
11286   * Operates on a subset of the fields: those in fields[fieldsStartIdx..].
11287   * @see collectshort(Object, String)
11288   */
11289  // @PolyNull does not work for return type, because null is returned on error.
11290  @SideEffectFree
11291  private static short @Nullable [] collectshort(@Nullable Object object,
11292                                                   String[] fields, int fieldsStartIdx) {
11293
11294    if (object == null) {
11295      return null;
11296    }
11297    assert (fields != null);
11298    assert (fieldsStartIdx >= 0 && fieldsStartIdx < fields.length);
11299
11300    Object fieldObj;
11301    try {
11302      Field field = (object instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
11303        ? ((Class<?>)object).getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx])
11304        : object.getClass().getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx]);
11305      field.setAccessible(true);
11306      // Class cls = field.getType();
11307      fieldObj = field.get(object);
11308      // System.out.println("***fieldObj="+fieldObj);
11309
11310    } catch (Exception e) {
11311      return null;
11312
11313    }
11314
11315    if (fieldObj == null) {
11316      return null;
11317    }
11318
11319    // base case: just accessed the last field
11320    if (fields.length - 1 == fieldsStartIdx) {
11321
11322      if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
11323        // last field is an array
11324        return (short[])fieldObj;
11325      } else {
11326        // This hack should be removed in favor of, at "oneEltArray = ..."
11327        // below, calling a version of collectshort_field that throws an
11328        // error.  Then, this case becomes a run-time error.  -MDE
11329
11330        // Just one element; return a one-element array.
11331        // assert cls.equals(Short.TYPE);
11332        return new short[] { ((Short)fieldObj).shortValue() };
11333      }
11334    } else {
11335      // recursive case: more fields to access after this one
11336
11337      if (daikon.ProglangType.list_implementors.contains(fieldObj.getClass().getName())) {
11338
11339        java.util.AbstractCollection<?> collection = (java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)fieldObj;
11340        short[] intermediate = new short[collection.size()];
11341        int index = 0;
11342        for (Iterator<?> i = collection.iterator() ; i.hasNext() ; ) {
11343          Object obj = i.next();
11344          short[] oneEltArray = collectshort(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
11345          if (oneEltArray == null) {
11346            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
11347          }
11348          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
11349          intermediate[index++] = oneEltArray[0];
11350        }
11351        return intermediate;
11352      } else if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
11353
11354        // collect elements across array
11355        short[] intermediate = new short[Array.getLength(fieldObj)];
11356        for (int i = 0 ; i < intermediate.length ; i++) {
11357          Object obj = Array.get(fieldObj, i);
11358          short[] oneEltArray = collectshort(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
11359          if (oneEltArray == null) {
11360            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
11361          }
11362          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
11363          intermediate[i] = oneEltArray[0];
11364        }
11365        return intermediate;
11366      } else {
11367
11368        return collectshort(fieldObj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
11369      }
11370    }
11371  }
11372
11373  /**
11374   * Returns the results of dereferencing the fields for 'object'. For example, the call
11375   *
11376   * <pre>collectshort_field(x, "f.g.h")</pre>
11377   *
11378   * has the same value as
11379   *
11380   * <pre>x.f.g.h</pre>.
11381   * Returns a default value if any field access causes an exception.
11382   */
11383  @SideEffectFree
11384  public static short collectshort_field(Object object, String fieldStr) {
11385
11386    if (object == null) {
11387      return Short.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
11388    }
11389    if (fieldStr == null) {
11390      return Short.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
11391    }
11392
11393    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
11394
11395    // Holds the intermediate (and final) result
11396    Object fieldObj = object;
11397
11398    for (int i = 0 ; i < fieldNames.length ; i++) {
11399
11400      String fieldName = fieldNames[i];
11401
11402      try {
11403        Field field =
11404          (fieldObj instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
11405          ? ((Class<?>)fieldObj).getDeclaredField(fieldName)
11406          : fieldObj.getClass().getDeclaredField(fieldName);
11407        field.setAccessible(true);
11408        fieldObj = field.get(fieldObj);
11409
11410        if (fieldObj == null) {
11411          return Short.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
11412        }
11413
11414      } catch (Exception e) {
11415        return Short.MAX_VALUE; // return default value
11416
11417      }
11418
11419    }
11420
11421    return ((Short)fieldObj).shortValue();
11422  }

11428  /**
11429   * Returns the ith element of the array or collection argument. If the argument is null or not an
11430   * array or collection, returns a default value (null).
11431   */
11432
11433  @SuppressWarnings("interning") // reflection
11434
11435  @Pure
11436  public static @Nullable @Interned Object getElement_Object(Object o, long i) {
11437    if (o == null) {
11438      return null; // return default value
11439    }
11440    java.lang.Class<?> c = o.getClass();
11441    if (c.isArray()) {
11442      return java.lang.reflect.Array.get(o, (int)i);
11443    } else if (o instanceof java.util.AbstractCollection<?>) {
11444      return java.lang.reflect.Array.get(((java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)o).toArray(), (int)i);
11445    } else {
11446      return null; // return default value
11447    }
11448  }

11456    }
11457    return arr[(int)i];
11458  }

11535   */
11536  @Pure
11537  public static @Interned Object @PolyNull [] intersection(@Interned Object @PolyNull [] seq1, @Interned Object @PolyNull [] seq2) {
11538    if (seq1 == null) {
11539      return null;
11540    }
11541    if (seq2 == null) {
11542      return null;
11543    }
11544    @Interned Object[] intermediate = new @Interned Object[Math.min(seq1.length, seq2.length)];
11545    int length = 0;
11546    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
11547      if (memberOf(seq1[i], seq2) ) {
11548        intermediate[length++] = seq1[i];
11549      }
11550    }
11551    return ArraysPlume.subarray(intermediate, 0, length);

11600  /** True iff seq1 is the reverse of seq2.
11601   *
11602   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
11603   *
11604   * <pre>
11605   * /\ seq1.length == seq2.length
11606   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq1.length-1 } : seq1[i] == seq2[seq2.length-1-i]
11607   * </pre>
11608   *
11609   */
11610  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
11611  @Pure
11612  public static boolean isReverse(@Interned Object[] seq1, @Interned Object[] seq2) {
11613    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
11614      return false;
11615    }
11616    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
11617    int length = seq1.length;
11618    for (int i = 0 ; i < length ; i++) {
11619      if (ne(seq1[i], seq2[length - i - 1])) {
11620        return false;
11621      }
11622    }
11623    return true;
11624  }

11709  @Pure
11710  public static @Interned Object @PolyNull [] slice(@Interned Object @PolyNull [] seq, int start, int end) {
11711    if (seq == null) {
11712      return null;
11713    }
11714    int sliceStart = start;
11715    int sliceEnd = end;
11716    if (start < 0) {
11717      return new @Interned Object[] { };
11718    }
11719    if (end > seq.length - 1) {
11720      return new @Interned Object[] { };
11721    }
11722    if (sliceStart > sliceEnd) {
11723      return new @Interned Object[] { };
11724    }
11725    int length = sliceEnd - sliceStart + 1;
11726    return ArraysPlume.subarray(seq, sliceStart, length);
11727  }

11784  /** True iff seq1 and seq2 have the same length, and every seq1[i] == seq2[i].

11809  @Pure
11810  public static boolean pairwiseEqual(@Nullable AbstractCollection<@Interned Object> seq1, @Interned Object @Nullable [] seq2) {

11815      return false;

11817    @SuppressWarnings("cast") // cast is redundant (except in JSR 308)
11818    @Interned Object[] seq1a = (@Interned Object[]) seq1.toArray(new @Interned Object[0]);
11819    return pairwiseEqual(seq1a, seq2);
11820  }

11836  /** True iff seq1 and seq2 have the same length, and every seq1[i] != seq2[i].
11837   *
11838   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
11839   *
11840   * /\ seq1.length == se2.length
11841   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq1.length-1 } : seq1[i] != seq2[i]
11842   *
11843   */
11844  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
11845  @Pure
11846  public static boolean pairwiseNotEqual(@Interned Object @Nullable [] seq1, @Interned Object @Nullable [] seq2) {
11847    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
11848      return false;
11849    }
11850    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
11851    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
11852      if (eq(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
11853        return false;
11854      }
11855    }
11856    return true;
11857  }

11895  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression="#1")
11896  @Pure
11897  public static boolean eltwiseEqual(@Interned Object @Nullable [] seq) {

11899    return false;
11900  }
11901    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq.length ; i++) {
11902      if (i < seq.length - 1) {
11903        if (ne(seq[i], seq[i + 1])) {
11904          return false;
11905        }
11906      }
11907    }
11908    return true;

11933
11934  /// Deferencing (accessing) fields
11935
11936  /**
11937   * collectObject accepts an object and a list of fields (one of which is of array type, and the
11938   * rest of which are not), and produces an array in which the original object has had the given
11939   * fields accessed.
11940   *
11941   * <p>Daikon creates invariants over "variables" such as the following.
11942   *
11943   * <dl>
11944   * <dt>x.arr[].z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements y.z
11945   *              for all y's in array x.arr.</dd>
11946   * <dt>arr[].y.z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements x.y.z
11947   *              for all x's in array arr.</dd>
11948   * <dt>x.y.z[]</dt>   <dd>The result of collecting all elements in array x.y.z[]</dd>
11949   * </dl>
11950   *
11951   * <p>The collectObject() method does this collecting work.
11952   *
11953   * <p>Given an object (x, arr, or x, correspondingly, in the above examples) and a "field string"
11954   * (arr.z, y.z, or y.z, correspondingly, in the above example), the collect method collects the
11955   * elements that result from following the fields, one of which is assumed to be an array.
11956   *
11957   * <p>
11958   * requires: fieldStr.length() &gt; 0 and object != null
11959   * <p>
11960   * requires: fieldStr contains only field names, no "[]" strings.
11961   * <p>
11962   * requires: the method only works for field sequences with exactly one field representing an
11963   * array. For example, the collection a[].b[].c will fail.
11964   *
11965   * @return if the resulting collection is of non-primitive type, then returns an array of type
11966   * Object[]. Returns null if any array or field access causes an exception.
11967   */
11968
11969  @SuppressWarnings("interning") // reflection
11970
11971  @SideEffectFree
11972  public static Object @Nullable [] collectObject(@Nullable Object object, @Nullable String fieldStr) {
11973
11974    if (object == null) {
11975      return null;
11976    }
11977    if (fieldStr == null) {
11978      return null;
11979    }
11980
11981    // assert fieldStr != null && !"".equals(fieldStr);
11982    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
11983    @Interned Object[] retval = collectObject(object, fieldNames, 0);
11984    // System.err.println("%%% fieldArray returned: " + plume.Arrays.toString(retval));
11985    return retval;
11986  }
11987
11988  @SuppressWarnings("interning") // reflection
11989
11990  /** Helper method for collectObject(Object, String).
11991   * Operates on a subset of the fields: those in fields[fieldsStartIdx..].
11992   * @see collectObject(Object, String)
11993   */
11994  // @PolyNull does not work for return type, because null is returned on error.
11995  @SideEffectFree
11996  private static Object @Nullable [] collectObject(@Nullable Object object,
11997                                                   String[] fields, int fieldsStartIdx) {
11998
11999    if (object == null) {
12000      return null;
12001    }
12002    assert (fields != null);
12003    assert (fieldsStartIdx >= 0 && fieldsStartIdx < fields.length);
12004
12005    Object fieldObj;
12006    try {
12007      Field field = (object instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
12008        ? ((Class<?>)object).getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx])
12009        : object.getClass().getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx]);
12010      field.setAccessible(true);
12011      // Class cls = field.getType();
12012      fieldObj = field.get(object);
12013      // System.out.println("***fieldObj="+fieldObj);
12014
12015    } catch (Exception e) {
12016      return null;
12017
12018    }
12019
12020    if (fieldObj == null) {
12021      return null;
12022    }
12023
12024    // base case: just accessed the last field
12025    if (fields.length - 1 == fieldsStartIdx) {
12026
12027      if (daikon.ProglangType.list_implementors.contains(fieldObj.getClass().getName())) {
12028        // last field is the collection
12029        @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
12030        java.util.AbstractCollection<@Interned Object> ac = (java.util.AbstractCollection<@Interned Object>)fieldObj;
12031        return ac.toArray(new @Interned Object[]{});
12032      } else
12033
12034      if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
12035        // last field is an array
12036        return (@Interned Object[])fieldObj;
12037      } else {
12038        // This hack should be removed in favor of, at "oneEltArray = ..."
12039        // below, calling a version of collectObject_field that throws an
12040        // error.  Then, this case becomes a run-time error.  -MDE
12041
12042        // Just one element; return a one-element array.
12043        // assert cls.equals(_TYPE_WRAPPER_NAME.TYPE);
12044        return new @Interned Object[] { fieldObj };
12045      }
12046    } else {
12047      // recursive case: more fields to access after this one
12048
12049      if (daikon.ProglangType.list_implementors.contains(fieldObj.getClass().getName())) {
12050
12051        java.util.AbstractCollection<?> collection = (java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)fieldObj;
12052        @Interned Object[] intermediate = new @Interned Object[collection.size()];
12053        int index = 0;
12054        for (Iterator<?> i = collection.iterator() ; i.hasNext() ; ) {
12055          Object obj = i.next();
12056          Object[] oneEltArray = collectObject(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
12057          if (oneEltArray == null) {
12058            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
12059          }
12060          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
12061          intermediate[index++] = oneEltArray[0];
12062        }
12063        return intermediate;
12064      } else if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
12065
12066        // collect elements across array
12067        @Interned Object[] intermediate = new @Interned Object[Array.getLength(fieldObj)];
12068        for (int i = 0 ; i < intermediate.length ; i++) {
12069          Object obj = Array.get(fieldObj, i);
12070          Object[] oneEltArray = collectObject(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
12071          if (oneEltArray == null) {
12072            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
12073          }
12074          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
12075          intermediate[i] = oneEltArray[0];
12076        }
12077        return intermediate;
12078      } else {
12079
12080        return collectObject(fieldObj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
12081      }
12082    }
12083  }
12084
12085  /**
12086   * Returns the results of dereferencing the fields for 'object'. For example, the call
12087   *
12088   * <pre>collectObject_field(x, "f.g.h")</pre>
12089   *
12090   * has the same value as
12091   *
12092   * <pre>x.f.g.h</pre>.
12093   * Returns a default value if any field access causes an exception.
12094   */
12095  @SideEffectFree
12096  public static @Nullable Object collectObject_field(Object object, String fieldStr) {
12097
12098    if (object == null) {
12099      return null; // return default value
12100    }
12101    if (fieldStr == null) {
12102      return null; // return default value
12103    }
12104
12105    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
12106
12107    // Holds the intermediate (and final) result
12108    Object fieldObj = object;
12109
12110    for (int i = 0 ; i < fieldNames.length ; i++) {
12111
12112      String fieldName = fieldNames[i];
12113
12114      try {
12115        Field field =
12116          (fieldObj instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
12117          ? ((Class<?>)fieldObj).getDeclaredField(fieldName)
12118          : fieldObj.getClass().getDeclaredField(fieldName);
12119        field.setAccessible(true);
12120        fieldObj = field.get(fieldObj);
12121
12122        if (fieldObj == null) {
12123          return null; // return default value
12124        }
12125
12126      } catch (Exception e) {
12127        return null; // return default value
12128
12129      }
12130
12131    }
12132
12133    return fieldObj;
12134  }

12140  /**
12141   * Returns the ith element of the array or collection argument. If the argument is null or not an
12142   * array or collection, returns a default value (null).
12143   */
12144
12145  @SuppressWarnings("interning") // reflection
12146
12147  @Pure
12148  public static @Nullable @Interned String getElement_String(Object o, long i) {
12149    if (o == null) {
12150      return null; // return default value
12151    }
12152    java.lang.Class<?> c = o.getClass();
12153    if (c.isArray()) {
12154      return (String)java.lang.reflect.Array.get(o, (int)i);
12155    } else if (o instanceof java.util.AbstractCollection<?>) {
12156      return (String)java.lang.reflect.Array.get(((java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)o).toArray(), (int)i);
12157    } else {
12158      return null; // return default value
12159    }
12160  }

12167      return null; // return default value
12168    }
12169    return arr[(int)i];
12170  }

12222  /**
12223   * Returns an array that is equivalent to the set intersection of seq1 and seq2. This method
12224   * gives no assurances about the order or repetition of elements: elements may be repeated, and
12225   * their order may be different from the order of elements in seq1 and seq2.
12226   */
12227  @Pure
12228  public static @Interned String @PolyNull [] intersection(@Interned String @PolyNull [] seq1, @Interned String @PolyNull [] seq2) {
12229    if (seq1 == null) {
12230      return null;
12231    }
12232    if (seq2 == null) {
12233      return null;
12234    }
12235    @Interned String[] intermediate = new @Interned String[Math.min(seq1.length, seq2.length)];
12236    int length = 0;
12237    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
12238      if (memberOf(seq1[i], seq2) ) {
12239        intermediate[length++] = seq1[i];
12240      }
12241    }
12242    return ArraysPlume.subarray(intermediate, 0, length);
12243  }

12250  @Pure

12256      return null;

12258    @Interned String[] intermediate = new @Interned String[seq1.length];

12291  /** True iff seq1 is the reverse of seq2.
12292   *
12293   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
12294   *
12295   * <pre>
12296   * /\ seq1.length == seq2.length
12297   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq1.length-1 } : seq1[i] == seq2[seq2.length-1-i]
12298   * </pre>
12299   *
12300   */
12301  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
12302  @Pure
12303  public static boolean isReverse(@Interned String[] seq1, @Interned String[] seq2) {
12304    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
12305      return false;
12306    }
12307    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
12308    int length = seq1.length;
12309    for (int i = 0 ; i < length ; i++) {
12310      if (ne(seq1[i], seq2[length - i - 1])) {
12311        return false;
12312      }
12313    }
12314    return true;
12315  }

12345 /** Returns true iff elt is in array arr. */
12346  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression="#2")

12349    if (arr == null) {
12350      return false;
12351    }

12353      if (eq(arr[i], elt)) {
12354        return true;

12357    return false;

12360  /** Returns a subsequence of seq with first elements seq[start] and last element seq[end]. */
12361  @Pure
12362  public static @Interned String @PolyNull [] slice(@Interned String @PolyNull [] seq, int start, int end) {
12363    if (seq == null) {
12364      return null;
12365    }
12366    int sliceStart = start;
12367    int sliceEnd = end;
12368    if (start < 0) {
12369      return new @Interned String[] { };
12370    }
12371    if (end > seq.length - 1) {
12372      return new @Interned String[] { };
12373    }
12374    if (sliceStart > sliceEnd) {
12375      return new @Interned String[] { };
12376    }
12377    int length = sliceEnd - sliceStart + 1;
12378    return ArraysPlume.subarray(seq, sliceStart, length);
12379  }

12436  /** True iff seq1 and seq2 have the same length, and every seq1[i] == seq2[i].
12437   *
12438   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
12439   *
12440   * /\ seq1.length == se2.length
12441   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq1.length-1 } : seq1[i] == seq2[i]
12442   *
12443   */
12444
12445  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
12446  @Pure
12447  public static boolean pairwiseEqual(@Interned String @Nullable [] seq1, @Interned String @Nullable [] seq2) {
12448    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
12449      return false;
12450    }
12451    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
12452    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
12453      if (ne(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
12454        return false;
12455      }
12456    }
12457    return true;
12458  }
12459
12460  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
12461  @Pure
12462  public static boolean pairwiseEqual(@Nullable AbstractCollection<@Interned String> seq1, @Interned String @Nullable [] seq2) {
12463    if (seq1 == null) {
12464      return false;
12465    }
12466    if (seq2 == null) {
12467      return false;
12468    }
12469    @SuppressWarnings("cast") // cast is redundant (except in JSR 308)
12470    @Interned String[] seq1a = (@Interned String[]) seq1.toArray(new @Interned String[0]);
12471    return pairwiseEqual(seq1a, seq2);
12472  }
12473
12474  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
12475  @Pure
12476  public static boolean pairwiseEqual(@Interned String @Nullable [] seq1, @Nullable AbstractCollection<@Interned String> seq2) {
12477    if (seq1 == null) {
12478      return false;
12479    }
12480    if (seq2 == null) {
12481      return false;
12482    }
12483    @SuppressWarnings("cast") // cast is redundant (except in JSR 308)
12484    @Interned String[] seq2a = (@Interned String[]) seq2.toArray();
12485    return pairwiseEqual(seq1, seq2a);
12486  }
12487
12488  /** True iff seq1 and seq2 have the same length, and every seq1[i] != seq2[i].
12489   *
12490   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
12491   *
12492   * /\ seq1.length == se2.length
12493   * /\ forall i in { 0..seq1.length-1 } : seq1[i] != seq2[i]
12494   *
12495   */
12496  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
12497  @Pure
12498  public static boolean pairwiseNotEqual(@Interned String @Nullable [] seq1, @Interned String @Nullable [] seq2) {
12499    if (!sameLength(seq1, seq2)) {
12500      return false;
12501    }
12502    assert seq1 != null && seq2 != null; // because sameLength() = true
12503    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq1.length ; i++) {
12504      if (eq(seq1[i], seq2[i])) {
12505        return false;
12506      }
12507    }
12508    return true;
12509  }

12511  /**
12512   * Returns true iff seq1 is lexically equal to seq2.
12513   * For equality, "lexically" and "pairwise" are the same.
12514   */
12515  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
12516  @Pure
12517  public static boolean lexEqual(@Interned String @Nullable [] seq1, @Interned String @Nullable [] seq2) {
12518    if (seq1 == null) {
12519      return false;
12520    }
12521    if (seq2 == null) {
12522      return false;
12523    }
12524    return pairwiseEqual(seq1, seq2);
12525  }
12526
12527  /** Returns true iff seq1 is lexically not equal to seq2. */
12528  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression={"#1","#2"})
12529  @Pure
12530  public static boolean lexNotEqual(@Interned String @Nullable [] seq1, @Interned String @Nullable [] seq2) {
12531    if (seq1 == null) {
12532      return false;
12533    }
12534    if (seq2 == null) {
12535      return false;
12536    }
12537    return !lexEqual(seq1, seq2);
12538  }

12540  /** True iff for all applicable i, every seq[i] == seq[i+1].
12541   *
12542   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
12543   *
12544   * forall i in { 0..seq.length-2 } : seq[i] == seq[i+1]
12545   *
12546   */
12547  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression="#1")
12548  @Pure
12549  public static boolean eltwiseEqual(@Interned String @Nullable [] seq) {
12550  if (seq == null) {
12551    return false;
12552  }
12553    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq.length ; i++) {
12554      if (i < seq.length - 1) {
12555        if (ne(seq[i], seq[i + 1])) {
12556          return false;
12557        }
12558      }
12559    }
12560    return true;
12561  }
12562
12563  /** True iff for all applicable i, every seq[i] != seq[i+1].
12564   *
12565   * Meaning (in pseudo-FOL):
12566   *
12567   * forall i in { 0..seq.length-2 } : seq[i] != seq[i+1]
12568   *
12569   */
12570  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression="#1")
12571  @Pure
12572  public static boolean eltwiseNotEqual(@Interned String @Nullable [] seq) {
12573  if (seq == null) {
12574    return false;
12575  }
12576    for (int i = 0 ; i < seq.length ; i++) {
12577      if (i < seq.length - 1) {
12578        if (eq(seq[i], seq[i + 1])) {
12579          return false;
12580        }
12581      }
12582    }
12583    return true;
12584  }
12585
12586  /// Deferencing (accessing) fields
12587
12588  /**
12589   * collectString accepts an object and a list of fields (one of which is of array type, and the
12590   * rest of which are not), and produces an array in which the original object has had the given
12591   * fields accessed.
12592   *
12593   * <p>Daikon creates invariants over "variables" such as the following.
12594   *
12595   * <dl>
12596   * <dt>x.arr[].z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements y.z
12597   *              for all y's in array x.arr.</dd>
12598   * <dt>arr[].y.z</dt> <dd>The result of collecting all elements x.y.z
12599   *              for all x's in array arr.</dd>
12600   * <dt>x.y.z[]</dt>   <dd>The result of collecting all elements in array x.y.z[]</dd>
12601   * </dl>
12602   *
12603   * <p>The collectString() method does this collecting work.
12604   *
12605   * <p>Given an object (x, arr, or x, correspondingly, in the above examples) and a "field string"
12606   * (arr.z, y.z, or y.z, correspondingly, in the above example), the collect method collects the
12607   * elements that result from following the fields, one of which is assumed to be an array.
12608   *
12609   * <p>
12610   * requires: fieldStr.length() &gt; 0 and object != null
12611   * <p>
12612   * requires: fieldStr contains only field names, no "[]" strings.
12613   * <p>
12614   * requires: the method only works for field sequences with exactly one field representing an
12615   * array. For example, the collection a[].b[].c will fail.
12616   *
12617   * @return if the resulting collection is of non-primitive type, then returns an array of type
12618   * Object[]. Returns null if any array or field access causes an exception.
12619   */
12620
12621  @SuppressWarnings("interning") // reflection
12622
12623  @SideEffectFree
12624  public static String @Nullable [] collectString(@Nullable Object object, @Nullable String fieldStr) {
12625
12626    if (object == null) {
12627      return null;
12628    }
12629    if (fieldStr == null) {
12630      return null;
12631    }
12632
12633    // assert fieldStr != null && !"".equals(fieldStr);
12634    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
12635    @Interned String[] retval = collectString(object, fieldNames, 0);
12636    // System.err.println("%%% fieldArray returned: " + plume.Arrays.toString(retval));
12637    return retval;
12638  }
12639
12640  @SuppressWarnings("interning") // reflection
12641
12642  /** Helper method for collectString(Object, String).
12643   * Operates on a subset of the fields: those in fields[fieldsStartIdx..].
12644   * @see collectString(Object, String)
12645   */
12646  // @PolyNull does not work for return type, because null is returned on error.
12647  @SideEffectFree
12648  private static String @Nullable [] collectString(@Nullable Object object,
12649                                                   String[] fields, int fieldsStartIdx) {
12650
12651    if (object == null) {
12652      return null;
12653    }
12654    assert (fields != null);
12655    assert (fieldsStartIdx >= 0 && fieldsStartIdx < fields.length);
12656
12657    Object fieldObj;
12658    try {
12659      Field field = (object instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
12660        ? ((Class<?>)object).getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx])
12661        : object.getClass().getDeclaredField(fields[fieldsStartIdx]);
12662      field.setAccessible(true);
12663      // Class cls = field.getType();
12664      fieldObj = field.get(object);
12665      // System.out.println("***fieldObj="+fieldObj);
12666
12667    } catch (Exception e) {
12668      return null;
12669
12670    }
12671
12672    if (fieldObj == null) {
12673      return null;
12674    }
12675
12676    // base case: just accessed the last field
12677    if (fields.length - 1 == fieldsStartIdx) {
12678
12679      if (daikon.ProglangType.list_implementors.contains(fieldObj.getClass().getName())) {
12680        // last field is the collection
12681        @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
12682        java.util.AbstractCollection<@Interned String> ac = (java.util.AbstractCollection<@Interned String>)fieldObj;
12683        return ac.toArray(new @Interned String[]{});
12684      } else
12685
12686      if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
12687        // last field is an array
12688        return (@Interned String[])fieldObj;
12689      } else {
12690        // This hack should be removed in favor of, at "oneEltArray = ..."
12691        // below, calling a version of collectString_field that throws an
12692        // error.  Then, this case becomes a run-time error.  -MDE
12693
12694        // Just one element; return a one-element array.
12695        // assert cls.equals(_TYPE_WRAPPER_NAME.TYPE);
12696        return new @Interned String[] { (String)fieldObj };
12697      }
12698    } else {
12699      // recursive case: more fields to access after this one
12700
12701      if (daikon.ProglangType.list_implementors.contains(fieldObj.getClass().getName())) {
12702
12703        java.util.AbstractCollection<?> collection = (java.util.AbstractCollection<?>)fieldObj;
12704        @Interned String[] intermediate = new @Interned String[collection.size()];
12705        int index = 0;
12706        for (Iterator<?> i = collection.iterator() ; i.hasNext() ; ) {
12707          Object obj = i.next();
12708          String[] oneEltArray = collectString(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
12709          if (oneEltArray == null) {
12710            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
12711          }
12712          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
12713          intermediate[index++] = oneEltArray[0];
12714        }
12715        return intermediate;
12716      } else if (fieldObj.getClass().isArray()) {
12717
12718        // collect elements across array
12719        @Interned String[] intermediate = new @Interned String[Array.getLength(fieldObj)];
12720        for (int i = 0 ; i < intermediate.length ; i++) {
12721          Object obj = Array.get(fieldObj, i);
12722          String[] oneEltArray = collectString(obj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
12723          if (oneEltArray == null) {
12724            throw new Error("bad fields: " + (obj == null ? "null" : obj.getClass()) + " " + Arrays.toString(fields) + " " + (fieldsStartIdx + 1));
12725          }
12726          // assert oneEltArray.length == 1;
12727          intermediate[i] = oneEltArray[0];
12728        }
12729        return intermediate;
12730      } else {
12731
12732        return collectString(fieldObj, fields, fieldsStartIdx + 1);
12733      }
12734    }
12735  }
12736
12737  /**
12738   * Returns the results of dereferencing the fields for 'object'. For example, the call
12739   *
12740   * <pre>collectString_field(x, "f.g.h")</pre>
12741   *
12742   * has the same value as
12743   *
12744   * <pre>x.f.g.h</pre>.
12745   * Returns a default value if any field access causes an exception.
12746   */
12747  @SideEffectFree
12748  public static @Nullable String collectString_field(Object object, String fieldStr) {
12749
12750    if (object == null) {
12751      return null; // return default value
12752    }
12753    if (fieldStr == null) {
12754      return null; // return default value
12755    }
12756
12757    String[] fieldNames = fieldStr.split("\\.");
12758
12759    // Holds the intermediate (and final) result
12760    Object fieldObj = object;
12761
12762    for (int i = 0 ; i < fieldNames.length ; i++) {
12763
12764      String fieldName = fieldNames[i];
12765
12766      try {
12767        Field field =
12768          (fieldObj instanceof java.lang.Class<?>)
12769          ? ((Class<?>)fieldObj).getDeclaredField(fieldName)
12770          : fieldObj.getClass().getDeclaredField(fieldName);
12771        field.setAccessible(true);
12772        fieldObj = field.get(fieldObj);
12773
12774        if (fieldObj == null) {
12775          return null; // return default value
12776        }
12777
12778      } catch (Exception e) {
12779        return null; // return default value
12780
12781      }
12782
12783    }
12784
12785    return (String)fieldObj;
12786  }

13067   */
13068  @SuppressWarnings("interning")  // cast from Object
13069  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression="#1")
13070  @Pure
13071  public static boolean eltsNotEqual(@Nullable Object arr, Object elt) {
13072    if (arr == null) {
13073      return false;
13074    }
13075    return eltsNotEqual(toObjArray(arr), elt);
13076  }
13077
13078  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression="#1")
13079  @Pure
13080  public static boolean isIntegralType(@Nullable Class<?> c) {
13081    if (c == null) {
13082      return false;
13083    }
13084    return
13085      (c.equals(Byte.TYPE)
13086       || c.equals(Short.TYPE)
13087       || c.equals(Integer.TYPE)
13088       || c.equals(Long.TYPE));
13089  }
13090
13091  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression="#1")
13092  @Pure
13093  public static boolean isRealType(@Nullable Class<?> c) {
13094    if (c == null) {
13095      return false;
13096    }
13097    return
13098      (c.equals(Float.TYPE)
13099       || c.equals(Double.TYPE));
13100  }
13101
13102  @EnsuresNonNullIf(result=true, expression="#1")
13103  @Pure
13104  public static boolean isNumericType(Class<?> c) {
13105    if (c == null) {
13106      return false;
13107    }
13108    return isIntegralType(c) || isRealType(c);
13109  }
13110
13111  /** Returns an Object[] array, either by casting or by conversion from an
13112   * AbstractCollection.
13113   */
13114  /*TODO: @AssertNonNullIfNonNull("#1")*/
13115  public static Object @PolyNull [] toObjArray(@PolyNull Object o) {
13116    if (o == null) {
13117      return null;
13118    }
13119    if (o instanceof java.util.AbstractCollection<?>) {
13120      @SuppressWarnings({"unchecked"})
13121        AbstractCollection<Object> ac = (AbstractCollection<Object>)o;
13122      Object [] result = ac.toArray(new java.lang.Object []{});
13123      return result;
13124    } else if (o.getClass().isArray()) {
13125      return (Object[])o;
13126    } else {
13127      throw new IllegalArgumentException("not an array or collection: " + o);
13128    }
13129  }
13130}
